 Tarrangower School,<ref name=\"official1982\">{{cite web |title=Tarrangower School Official School Website |url=http://www.tarrangower.school.nz |website=tarrangower.school.nz}}</ref><ref name=\"moe1982\">{{cite web |title=Tarrangower School Ministry of Education School Profile |url=https://www.educationcounts.govt.nz/find-school/school/profile?school=1982 |website=educationcounts.govt.nz |publisher=[[Ministry of Education (New Zealand)|Ministry of Education]]}}</ref> with a roll of {{NZ school roll data|1982|y}},<ref name=\"ero1982\">{{cite web |title=Tarrangower School Education Review Office Report |url=http://www.ero.govt.nz/report-view?id=1982 |website=ero.govt.nz |publisher=[[Education Review Office]]}}</ref> and Turaki School,<ref name=\"official2040\">{{cite web |title=Turaki School Official School Website |url=http://www.turakiprimary.school.nz |website=turakiprimary.school.nz}}</ref><ref name=\"moe2040\">{{cite web |title=Turaki School Ministry of Education School Profile |url=https://www.educationcounts.govt.nz/find-school/school/profile?school=2040 |website=educationcounts.govt.nz |publisher=[[Ministry of Education (New Zealand)|Ministry of Education]]}}</ref> with a roll of {{NZ school roll data|2040|y}}.<ref name=\"ero2040\">{{cite web |title=Turaki School Education Review Office Report |url=http://www.ero.govt.nz/report-view?id=2040 |website=ero.govt.nz |publisher=[[Education Review Office]]}}</ref>\n\nSt Patrick's Catholic School is a co-educational state-integrated Catholic primary school for Year 1 to 8 students,<ref name=\"moe1961\">{{cite web |title=Ministry of Education School Profile |url=https://www.educationcounts.govt.nz/find-school/school/profile?school=1961 |website=educationcounts.govt.nz |publisher=[[Ministry of Education (New Zealand)|Ministry of Education]]}}</ref> with a roll of {{NZ school roll data|1961|y}}.<ref name=\"ero1961\">{{cite web |title=Education Review Office Report |url=http://www.ero.govt.nz/report-view?id=1961 |website=ero.govt.nz |publisher=[[Education Review Office]]}}</ref>\n\n== Notable people==\n* T.J. Meredith \u2013  great-grandson of [[Theodore of Corsica]], joined [[Royal Navy]] age 14, [[CSS Louisiana]] in 1862 [[American Civil War]], under [[Duncan Alexander Cameron|General Cameron]] [[New Zealand Wars]], [[Waikato Mounted Rifles]] [[World War I]], before coming the proprietor of Taumarunui's Meredith House with wife Margaret Lovett.<ref>[[#Craig1990|Craig 1990]], T.J. Meredith p.147</ref>\n\n===Students of Taumarunui High School===\n* Prof. James L. Beck<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.its.caltech.edu/~jimbeck/ |title=James L. Beck |publisher=Its.caltech.edu |date= |accessdate=2013-10-23}}</ref> \u2013 Professor of Engineering and Applied Science, [[California Institute of Technology]].\n* Prof. [[John C. Butcher]] {{post-nominals|country=NZL|ONZM}} <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.math.auckland.ac.nz/~butcher/ |title=John Butcher's Homepage |publisher=Math.auckland.ac.nz |accessdate=2013-10-23}}</ref> \u2013 Honorary Research Professor, Dept. of Mathematics, [[University of Auckland]].\n* [[Ben Fouhy]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.benfouhy.com|title=Ben Fouhy : Words|publisher=Benfouhy.com|accessdate=2013-10-23}}</ref> world champion kayaker.\n* [[Marc Hunter|Marc]] and [[Todd Hunter]] from the band [[Dragon (band)|Dragon]].\n* [[Ivan Mercep]], 2008 recipient of the [[New Zealand Institute of Architects]] Gold Medal.\n* [[Jenny Ludlam]] \u2013  actress.\n\n===Born in Taumarunui===\n[[File:Carmen Rupe.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Carmen Rupe]]]]\n* 1914 \u2013 [[Wiremu Te Awhitu|Wiremu Hakopa Toa Te Awhitu SM]] (1914\u20131994) was the first M\u0101ori to be ordained a [[Catholic]] priest.\n* 1935 \u2013 [[Don Selwyn]], Actor, Director, Stage and Screen, [[Ng\u0101ti Kuri]] and [[Te Aup\u014duri]] (1935\u20132007) <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thearts.co.nz/artist_page.php&aid=5&type=bio |title=The Arts Foundation : Don Selwyn \u2013 Biography |publisher=Thearts.co.nz |date= |accessdate=2015-01-18}}</ref>\n* 1936 \u2013 [[Carmen Rupe]] (n\u00e9 Trevor Rupe, 1935\u201315 December 2011) \u2013 [[Wellington]] personality (mayoral candidate (1977), drag queen, cafe owner and brothel keeper).<ref>{{cite news |first=Shabnam |last=Dastgheib |title=Birthday girl Carmen hits town |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/life-style/2946328/Birthday-girl-Carmen-hits-town/ |work=[[The Dominion Post (Wellington)|The Dominion Post]] |date=9 October 2009 |accessdate=16 December 2011}}</ref>{{sfn|O'Keefe and Fox|2008|p=249}}<ref>{{cite news |title=Colourful Wellington identity Carmen dies |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/6142914/Colourful-Wellington-identity-Carmen-dies |work=[[The Dominion Post (Wellington)|The Dominion Post]] |date=15 December 2011 |accessdate=15 December 2011}}</ref>\n* 1939 \u2013 [[David Penny]], theoretical biologist.<ref name=\"massey1\">{{cite web|title=Professor Emeritus joins prominent US Academy|url=http://www.massey.ac.nz/massey/about-massey/news/article.cfm?mnarticle_uuid=FB8FD7F2-72A8-4181-A614-B9CD5D999D92|publisher=Massey University|accessdate=30 January 2019}}</ref>\n* 1945 \u2013 [[Carole Shepheard]], artist.\n* 1951 \u2013 [[Joe Karam]], rugby union player, researcher and investigator for [[David Bain]]'s legal team.\n* 1952 \u2013 [[Ian Ferguson (canoeist)|Ian Ferguson]], Olympic canoer.\n* 1952 \u2013 [[Max Mariu|Max Takuira Matthew Mariu SM]] (1952\u20132005), Auxiliary Catholic Bishop of Hamilton (1988\u20132005), first [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]] to be ordained a Catholic bishop.\n* 1953 \u2013 [[Marc Hunter]], lead singer of [[Dragon (band)|Dragon]].\n* 1955 \u2013 [[Mahin\u0101rangi Tocker]], singer. \n* 1956 \u2013 [[Len Brown]] Mayor of Auckland\n* 1958 \u2013 [[Jillian Smith]], field hockey player.\n* 1958 \u2013 [[Lindsay Crocker]], cricketer.\n* 1960s [[Timothy J. Sinclair]], political scientist.\n* 1971 \u2013 [[Kyle Chapman]], former leader of the [[New Zealand National Front]]\n* 1973 \u2013 [[Chris McCormack (triathlete)|Chris McCormack]] World Champion Ironman Triathlete (2007, 2010).\n\n=== Resident and New Years Honours recipients===\n[[File:PeiTeHurinuiJones1930.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Pei Te Hurinui Jones]]]]\n* [[1956 New Year Honours|1956]] \u2013 [[Order of the British Empire#Officer of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire|OBE]] \u2013 Pateriki Joseph Hura \u2013 For services to the M\u0101ori people, especially as a member of the Board of Maori Affairs.\n* [[1957 New Year Honours|1957]] \u2013 [[Order of the British Empire#Member of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire|MBE]] \u2013 Mrs Catherine Goodsir \u2013 For social welfare services\n* [[1958 New Year Honours|1958]] \u2013 MBE \u2013 [[Rumatiki Ruth Wright|Mrs Rumatiki Wright]] of Raetihi. For services to the M\u0101ori people, especially as Senior Lady M\u0101ori Welfare Officer\n* [[1961 New Year Honours|1961]] \u2013 OBE \u2013 [[Pei Te Hurinui Jones]] \u2013 For services to the M\u0101ori people.\n* [[1967 New Year Honours|1967]] \u2013 MBE \u2013 James Dempsey [[Justice of the peace#New Zealand|J.P.]] \u2013  chairman of the Taumarunui [[Counties of New Zealand|County Council]].\n* [[1970 New Year Honours|1970]] \u2013 [[British Empire Medal|BEM]] \u2013 Eric Raymond Clark \u2013 For services to the community and interest in the education of the M\u0101ori people.\n* [[1974 New Year Honours|1974]] \u2013 BEM \u2013 Arthur Tukiri Anderson \u2013 For services to the Returned Services Association and the community\n* [[1979 New Year Honours|1979]] \u2013 [[Order of the British Empire#Knight Commander or Dame Commander of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire|KBE]] \u2013 [[Hepi Te Heuheu|Hepi Hoani Te Heuheu]] \u2013 For services to the M\u0101ori people and community.\n* [[1995 New Year Honours|1995]] \u2013 [[Order of the British Empire#Commander of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire|CBE]] \u2013 Alexander Phillips QSM \u2013 For services to the M\u0101ori people.\n* [[1998 New Year Honours|1998]] \u2013 [[New Zealand Order of Merit#Member|MNZM]] \u2013 John Stacey Black J.P. \u2013 For services to the community.\n* [[2000 New Year Honours|2000]] \u2013 [[Queen's Service Medal|QSM]] \u2013 Jean Bassett \u2013 For Community Service\n* [[2001 New Year Honours|2001]] \u2013 QSM \u2013 Mrs Verna Lenice Warner J.P. \u2013 For Community Service\n* [[2002 New Year Honours|2002]] \u2013 MNZM \u2013 Mrs Nansi Whetu Dewes \u2013 For services to M\u0101ori and the community\n* [[2002 New Year Honours|2002]] \u2013 QSM \u2013 Barry David FISHER, of Taumarunui. Chief Fire Officer, Taumarunui Volunteer Fire Brigade, New Zealand Fire Service \u2013 For Services to the community\n* [[2003 New Year Honours|2003]] \u2013 QSM \u2013 Leonard Patrick Harwood \u2013 For Public Services\n* [[2007 New Year Honours|2007]] \u2013 QSM \u2013 Mr William Vernon McMinn \u2013 For services to music.\n* [[2009 New Year Honours|2009]] \u2013 MNZM \u2013 Ngarau Tarawa \u2013  For services to M\u0101ori and community education\n* [[2010 New Year Honours|2010]] \u2013 QSM \u2013 Mrs Lorraine Ivy Edwards J.P. \u2013 For services to the community.\n* [[2012 New Year Honours|2012]] \u2013 MNZM \u2013 Ian Trevor Corney \u2013 For services to agriculture\n* [[2013 New Year Honours|2013]] \u2013 [[New Zealand Order of Merit#Officer|ONZM]] \u2013 Susan May Morris \u2013 For services to local government.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|3}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book |last=Craig |first=Dick |title=The King Country |year=1990 |publisher=Waitomo News |location=Waitomo |ref=Craig1990}}\n*{{cite book |last1=O'Keefe | first1=Tracie | first2=Katrina | last2=Fox | title=[[Trans People in Love]] | publisher=Routledge |date=6 June 2008 |chapter=Chapter 24: Madam Carmen \u2013 Carmen Rupe |isbn=978-0-7890-3572-1 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/?id=AigQSatPMgAC |ref = {{sfnRef|O'Keefe and Fox|2008|p=249}}}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Taumarunui}}\n* [https://www.taumarunui.co.nz Taumarunui website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050408235349/http://www.ruapehutourism.co.nz/TAUMARUNUI_HISTORY.htm Local History]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070630215030/http://www.taumarunuihigh.school.nz/ Taumarunui High School]\n* [http://www.riverboats.homestead.com/RiverboatLandings.html River Boat Landings]\n* [http://folksong.org.nz/taumarunui/index.html Peter Cape]'s song, \"Taumarunui on the Main Trunk Line\"\n\n{{Ruapehu_District}}\n{{Whanganui}}\n{{The Overlander train stops}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Manawat\u016b-Whanganui]]\n[[Category:Settlements on the Whanganui River]]\n[[Category:Ruapehu District]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "ref name fixedWP:REFNAME", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taumarunui"}
{"title_page": "Stremma", "text_new": "The '''stremma''' ({{abbr|pl.|plural}}&nbsp;stremmata; {{lang-grc-grk|\u03c3\u03c4\u03c1\u03ad\u03bc\u03bc\u03b1}}, ''str\u00e9mma'') is a [[Greece|Greek]] unit of land [[area]] now equal to precisely 1,000 [[square meter]]s. Its area can be visualized as equal to the area enclosed by a square having side length of 31.62 meters, or 103.7 imperial [[Foot (unit)|feet]]. \n__NOTOC__\n\n==History==\nThe [[Ancient Greece|ancient Greek]] [[Greek units|equivalent]] was the [[square&nbsp;plethron]], which served as the Greeks' form of the [[acre (unit)|acre]]. It was originally defined as the distance plowed by a team of [[ox]]en in a day<ref>{{Citation |last=Pryce |first=Frederick Norman |author2-last=Lang |author2-first=Mabel L. |author3-last=Vickers |author3-first=Michael |display-authors=1 |editor-last=Spawforth |editor-first=Antony |editor2-last=Hornblower |editor2-first=Simon |editor3-last=Eidinow |editor3-first=Esther |display-editors=0 |contribution=measures |contribution-url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=bVWcAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA917 |title=The Oxford Classical Dictionary, ''4th&nbsp;ed.'' |p=917 |location=Oxford |publisher=Oxford University Press |date=2012 |isbn=978-0-19-954556-8 |ref={{harvid|Pryce|2012}} }}.</ref> but nominally standardized as the area enclosed by a square 100&nbsp;[[Greek feet]] (''[[pous]]'') to a side. This area was also used as the size of a [[Greek wrestling]] square.\n\nThe '''[[Byzantine units|Byzantine]]''' or '''[[Morea]]n&nbsp;stremma''' continued to vary depending on the period and the quality of the land, but usually enclosed an area between {{convert|900|-|1900|m2|sp=us|abbr=on}}.<ref>Siriol Davis, \"Pylos Regional Archaeological Project, Part VI: administration and settlement in Venetian Navarino\", ''Hesperia'', Winter, 2004 [http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0SDG/is_1_73/ai_n13493303/pg_17]</ref> It was originally also known as the \"plethron\" but this was eventually replaced by \"stremma\", derived from the verb for \"turning\" the ground with the simple Byzantine plow.<ref>\u039b\u03b5\u03be\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03ba\u03bf\u03b9\u03bd\u03ae\u03c2 \u039d\u03b5\u03bf\u03b5\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 (Dictionary of Modern Greek), \u0399\u03bd\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03c4\u03bf\u03cd\u03c4\u03bf \u039d\u03b5\u03bf\u03b5\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03ce\u03bd \u03a3\u03c0\u03bf\u03c5\u03b4\u03ce\u03bd, \u0398\u03b5\u03c3\u03c3\u03b1\u03bb\u03bf\u03bd\u03af\u03ba\u03b7, 1998. {{ISBN|960-231-085-5}}</ref>\n\nThe '''old''', '''[[Turkish units of measurement|Turkish]]''', or '''[[Ottoman units of measurement|Ottoman]]&nbsp;stremma''' is the Greek (and occasionally English) name for the \"[[dunam]]\", which probably derived from the Byzantine unit.<ref>V.L. M\u00e9nage, Review of Speros Vryonis, Jr. ''The decline of medieval Hellenism in Asia Minor and the process of islamization from the eleventh through the fifteenth century'', Berkeley, 1971; in ''Bulletin of the School of Oriental and African Studies'' (University of London) '''36''':3 (1973), pp. 659-661. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/613605 at JSTOR (subscription required)]; see also Erich Schilbach, ''Byzantinische Metrologie''.</ref> Again, this varied by region: ''The Dictionary of Modern Greek'' gives a value of {{convert|1,270|m2|sp=us|abbr=on}},<ref>\u039b\u03b5\u03be\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc, 1998</ref> but [[Costas Lapavitsas]] used the value of 1,600 m<sup>2</sup> for the region of [[Naousa, Imathia|Naoussa]] in the early 20th century.<ref>[[Costas Lapavitsas]], {{cite web|url=http://eprints.soas.ac.uk/8828/1/Lapavitsas4112005.pdf |journal=\u0397\u03bb\u03b5\u03ba\u03c4\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u0394\u03b5\u03bb\u03c4\u03af\u03bf \u039f\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03bc\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u0399\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c1\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 |title=Social and Economic Underpinning of Industrial Development: Evidence from Ottoman Macedonia |accessdate=2012-08-29|df= }}</ref>\n\n==Conversions==\nOne modern stremma is equivalent to:\n\n;Metric\n* 1,000 [[square metres]]\n* 10 [[hectare#Are|are]]s\n* 1 [[decare]]\n* 0.1 [[hectare]]\n* 0.001 [[square kilometre]]s\n\n;Imperial\n* 10,763.9 [[square foot|square feet]]\n* 0.247 105 38 [[acre]]s\n* 0.247 104 39 [[U.S. survey acre]]s (1 acre \u2248 4.047 stremmata)\n* 0.000 386 102 [[square mile]]s\n\n==See also==\n*[[1 E3 m\u00b2]] for further comparisons\n* [[Byzantine units]]\n*[[Conversion of units]]\n* [[Greek units]]\n* [[Metric units]]\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Units of area]]\n[[Category:Human-based units of measurement]]\n[[Category:Metricated units]]\n", "text_old": "The '''stremma''' ({{abbr|pl.|plural}}&nbsp;stremmata; {{lang-grc-grk|\u03c3\u03c4\u03c1\u03ad\u03bc\u03bc\u03b1}}, ''str\u00e9mma'') is a [[Greece|Greek]] unit of land [[area]] now equal to precisely 1,000 [[square meter]]s. Its area can be visualized as equal to the area enclosed by a square having side length of 31.62 meters, or 103.7 imperial [[Foot (unit)|feet]]. \n__NOTOC__\n\n==History==\nThe [[Ancient Greece|ancient Greek]] [[Greek units|equivalent]] was the [[square&nbsp;plethron]], which served as the Greeks' form of the [[acre (unit)|acre]]. It was originally defined as the distance plowed by a team of [[ox]]en in a day<ref>{{Citation |last=Pryce |first=Frederick Norman |author2-last=Lang |author2-first=Mabel L. |author3-last=Vickers |author3-first=Michael |display-authors=1 |editor-last=Spawforth |editor-first=Antony |editor2-last=Hornblower |editor2-first=Simon |editor3-last=Eidinow |editor3-first=Esther |display-editors=0 |contribution=measures |contribution-url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=bVWcAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA917 |title=The Oxford Classical Dictionary, ''4th&nbsp;ed.'' |p=917 |location=Oxford |publisher=Oxford University Press |date=2012 |isbn=978-0-19-954556-8 |ref={{harvid|Pryce|2012}} }}.</ref> but nominally standardized as the area enclosed by a square 100&nbsp;[[Greek feet]] (''[[pous]]'') to a side. This area was also used as the size of a [[Greek wrestling]] square.\n\nThe '''[[Byzantine units|Byzantine]]''' or '''[[Morea]]n&nbsp;stremma''' continued to vary depending on the period and the quality of the land, but usually enclosed an area between {{convert|900|-|1900|m2|sp=us|abbr=on}}.<ref>Siriol Davis, \"Pylos Regional Archaeological Project, Part VI: administration and settlement in Venetian Navarino\", ''Hesperia'', Winter, 2004 [http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0SDG/is_1_73/ai_n13493303/pg_17]</ref> It was originally also known as the \"plethron\" but this was eventually replaced by \"stremma\", derived from the verb for \"turning\" the ground with the simple Byzantine plow.<ref>\u039b\u03b5\u03be\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03ba\u03bf\u03b9\u03bd\u03ae\u03c2 \u039d\u03b5\u03bf\u03b5\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 (Dictionary of Modern Greek), \u0399\u03bd\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03c4\u03bf\u03cd\u03c4\u03bf \u039d\u03b5\u03bf\u03b5\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03ce\u03bd \u03a3\u03c0\u03bf\u03c5\u03b4\u03ce\u03bd, \u0398\u03b5\u03c3\u03c3\u03b1\u03bb\u03bf\u03bd\u03af\u03ba\u03b7, 1998. {{ISBN|960-231-085-5}}</ref>\n\nThe '''old''', '''[[Turkish units of measurement|Turkish]]''', or '''[[Ottoman units of measurement|Ottoman]]&nbsp;stremma''' is the Greek (and occasionally English) name for the \"[[dunam]]\", which probably derived from the Byzantine unit.<ref>V.L. M\u00e9nage, Review of Speros Vryonis, Jr. ''The decline of medieval Hellenism in Asia Minor and the process of islamization from the eleventh through the fifteenth century'', Berkeley, 1971; in ''Bulletin of the School of Oriental and African Studies'' (University of London) '''36''':3 (1973), pp. 659-661. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/613605 at JSTOR (subscription required)]; see also Erich Schilbach, ''Byzantinische Metrologie''.</ref> Again, this varied by region: ''The Dictionary of Modern Greek'' gives a value of {{convert|1,270|m2|sp=us|abbr=on}},<ref>\u039b\u03b5\u03be\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc, 1998</ref> but [[Costas Lapavitsas]] used the value of 1,600 m<sup>2</sup> for the region of [[Naousa, Imathia|Naoussa]] in the early 20th century.<ref>[[Costas Lapavitsas]], {{cite web|url=http://eprints.soas.ac.uk/8828/1/Lapavitsas4112005.pdf |journal=\u0397\u03bb\u03b5\u03ba\u03c4\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u0394\u03b5\u03bb\u03c4\u03af\u03bf \u039f\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03bc\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u0399\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c1\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 |title=Social and Economic Underpinning of Industrial Development: Evidence from Ottoman Macedonia |accessdate=2012-08-29|df= }}</ref>\n\n==Conversions==\nOne modern stremma is equivalent to:\n\n;Metric\n* 1,000 [[square metres]]\n* 10 [[hectare#Are|are]]s\n* 1 [[decare]]\n* 0.1 [[hectare]]\n* 0.001 [[square kilometre]]s\n\n;Imperial\n* 10,763.9 [[square foot|square feet]]\n* 0.247 105 38 [[acre]]s\n* 0.247 104 39 [[U.S. survey acre]]s (1 acre \u2248 4.047 stremmata)\n* 0.000 386 102 [[square mile]]s\n\n==See also==\n*[[1 E3 m\u00b2]] for further comparisons\n* [[Byzantine units]]\n*[[Conversion of units]]\n* [[Greek units]]\n* [[Metric units]]\n* Streema ([[streaming radio]])\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Units of area]]\n[[Category:Human-based units of measurement]]\n[[Category:Metricated units]]\n", "name_user": "Dondervogel 2", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also:not relevant to article", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stremma"}
{"title_page": "Terence Stamp", "text_new": "{{short description|British actor}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2010}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Terence Stamp\n| image = Terence Stamp.2794.jpg\n| caption = Stamp at the [[Valkyrie (film)|Valkyrie]] premiere in Berlin, 2009\n| birth_name = Terence Henry Stamp\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1938|7|22|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Stepney]], [[London]], England\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| occupation = Actor\n| years_active = 1962\u2013present\n| spouse = {{marriage|Elizabeth O'Rourke|2002|2008|reason=divorced}}\n| relatives = [[Chris Stamp]] (brother; deceased)\n}}\n\n'''Terence Henry Stamp''' (born 22 July 1938)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=BRGIjhAqTGTw%2FEId%2FJFxkg&scan=1 |title=Index entry |work=[[FreeBMD]] |publisher=ONS |accessdate=15 February 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"filmr\">{{cite web |url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/99/Terence-Stamp.html |title=Terence Stamp Biography (1938?-) |website=FilmReference.com |date= |accessdate=30 September 2010}}</ref> is an English actor. After training at the [[Webber Douglas Academy of Dramatic Art]] in London he started his acting career in 1962. Regarded as a \u201cmaster of the brooding silence\u201d by ''The Guardian'', Stamp has appeared in more than 60 films.<ref name=\"Stamp best\"/> His performance in the title role of ''[[Billy Budd (film)|Billy Budd]]'', his film debut, earned him an [[Academy Award]] nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] and a [[BAFTA Award|BAFTA]] nomination for [[BAFTA Award for Best Newcomer|Best Newcomer]]. Associated with the [[swinging London]] scene of the 1960s \u2013 during which time he was in a high-profile relationship with [[Julie Christie]] \u2013 Stamp was among the subjects photographed by [[David Bailey]] for a set titled ''Box of Pin-Ups''.<ref>{{cite book |first=Christopher |last=Bray |title=1965: The Year Modern Britain was Born |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8XwyAQAAQBAJ&pg=PT195 |year=2014 |publisher=Simon & Schuster |location=London |page=xii |isbn=978-1-84983-387-5}}</ref>\n\nStamp played butterfly collector Freddie Clegg in ''[[The Collector (1965 film)|The Collector]]'' (1965), and in 1967 appeared in ''[[Far from the Madding Crowd (1967 film)|Far from the Madding Crowd]]'', starring opposite Christie. His other major roles include playing archvillain [[General Zod]] in ''[[Superman (1978 film)|Superman]]'' and ''[[Superman II]]'', tough guy Wilson in ''[[The Limey]]'', [[Supreme Chancellor Valorum]] in ''[[Star Wars: Episode I \u2013 The Phantom Menace]]'', transgender woman Bernadette Bassinger in ''[[The Adventures of Priscilla, Queen of the Desert]]'', ghost antagonist Ramsley in ''[[The Haunted Mansion (film)|The Haunted Mansion]]'', [[Stick (comics)|Stick]] in ''[[Elektra (2005 film)|Elektra]]'', Pekwarsky in ''[[Wanted (2008 film)|Wanted]]'', Siegfried in ''[[Get Smart (film)|Get Smart]]'', Terrence Bundley in ''[[Yes Man (film)|Yes Man]]'', the Prophet of Truth in ''[[Halo 3]]'', Mankar Camoran in ''[[The Elder Scrolls IV: Oblivion]]'', and General [[Ludwig Beck]] in ''[[Valkyrie (film)|Valkyrie]]''. He has appeared in [[List of frequent Tim Burton collaborators|two Tim Burton films]], ''[[Big Eyes]]'' (2014) and ''[[Miss Peregrine's Home for Peculiar Children (film)|Miss Peregrine's Home for Peculiar Children]]'' (2016).\n\nFor his acting, Stamp has won a [[Golden Globe]], a Mystfest, a [[Cannes Film Festival]] Award, a [[Seattle International Film Festival]] Award, a [[Satellite Award]], and a [[Silver Bear]]. Stamp has also had voice work, narrating ''[[Jazz Britannia]]'' on the [[BBC]], and ''1966 \u2013 A Nation Remembers'' on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] in July 2016 which marked the 50th anniversary of England's [[1966 FIFA World Cup]] victory.\n\n==Early life==\nStamp, the eldest of five children, was born in [[Stepney]], [[London]], England, the son of Ethel Esther (n\u00e9e Perrott; 1914\u20131987) and Thomas Stamp (1912\u20131982), who was a [[tugboat]] stoker.<ref name=\"filmr\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/contributor/1800014689/bio |title=Terence Stamp Biography |website=Yahoo! Movies |date= |accessdate=30 September 2010}}</ref> His early years were spent in Canal Road, [[Bow, London|Bow]],<ref>Internet Movie Database.</ref> in the [[East End of London|East End]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://observer.guardian.co.uk/foodmonthly/story/0,,662828,00.html |title=Mr Intolerant |first=Caroline |last=Boucher |date=10 March 2002 |work=[[The Observer]] |location=London |accessdate=25 May 2010}}</ref> but later in his childhood the family moved to [[Plaistow, Newham|Plaistow]], [[County Borough of West Ham|West Ham]], [[Essex]] (now in [[Greater London]]), where he attended [[Plaistow County Grammar School]]. His father was away for long periods with the [[British Merchant Navy|Merchant Navy]] and the young Stamp was mostly brought up by his mother, grandmother, and aunts. He grew up idolising actor [[Gary Cooper]] after his mother took him to see ''[[Beau Geste (1939 film)|Beau Geste]]'' (1939) when he was three years old. He was also inspired by the 1950s [[Method acting|method-trained]] actor [[James Dean]].\n\nAfter leaving school, Stamp worked in a variety of [[Advertising agency|advertising agencies]] in London, working his way up to earning a reasonable salary. In the mid\u20111950s, he also worked as an assistant to professional golfer Reg Knight at [[Wanstead]] Golf Club in [[east London]]. He describes this period of his life positively in his autobiography ''Stamp Album''.<ref name=\"StampAlbum\">{{cite book |last=Stamp |first=Terence |date=1987 |title=Stamp Album |location=London |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing |isbn=978-0-74750-032-2}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n=== Early career and rise to fame ===\nStamp won a [[scholarship]] to train at the [[Webber Douglas Academy of Dramatic Art]], then performed in various provincial [[repertory theatre]]s,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://escargotbooksonline.com/author_terence_stamp_ebook.php |title=Terence Stamp Biography |work=Escargot Books |year=2011 |accessdate=26 November 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120120101002/http://escargotbooksonline.com/author_terence_stamp_ebook.php |archivedate=20 January 2012}}</ref> most notably in a national tour of [[Willis Hall]]'s play ''[[The Long and the Short and the Tall (play)|The Long the Short and the Tall]]'' alongside another young cockney actor [[Michael Caine]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.silksoundbooks.com/performers/terence-stamp/ |title=Terence Stamp reads audio books |work=Silk Sound Books |year=2011 |accessdate=26 November 2011}}</ref> Caine moved in with Stamp, and they began hanging out with [[Peter O'Toole]] in the London party scene.<ref name=\"Caine 2019\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.ie/entertainment/movies/michael-caine-tales-of-a-jobbing-cockney-34385708.html |title=Michael Caine: Tales of a jobbing cockney |date=24 January 2016 |newspaper=[[Irish Independent]] |access-date=7 February 2019}}</ref> Stamp made his film debut in [[Peter Ustinov]]'s film adaptation of [[Herman Melville]]'s ''[[Billy Budd (film)|Billy Budd]]'' (1962). His portrayal of the title character brought him not only an [[Academy Award]] nomination but also international attention. He then appeared opposite [[Laurence Olivier]] in ''[[Term of Trial]]'' (1962).\n[[File:Monica Vitti en Terence Stamp (1965).jpg|thumb|right|Stamp with actress [[Monica Vitti]] in 1965 during filming ''[[Modesty Blaise (1966 film)|Modesty Blaise]]'']] \nStamp collaborated with some of the most revered filmmakers. He starred in [[William Wyler]]'s adaptation of [[John Fowles]]' ''[[The Collector]]'' (1965), opposite [[Samantha Eggar]], and in ''[[Modesty Blaise (1966 film)|Modesty Blaise]]'' (1966), for director [[Joseph Losey]] and producer Joe Janni. Stamp reunited with producer Janni for two more projects: [[John Schlesinger]]'s adaptation of [[Thomas Hardy]]'s ''[[Far from the Madding Crowd (1967 film)|Far from the Madding Crowd]]'' (1967) starring [[Julie Christie]], and [[Ken Loach]]'s first feature film ''[[Poor Cow]]'' (1967).\n\nHe was approached to play the role of [[James Bond]] when [[Sean Connery]] retired from the role,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/showbiz/celebrity-news/terence-stamp-i-blew-the-chance-to-play-james-bond-8608829.html |title=Terence Stamp: I blew the chance to play James Bond |last1=Foster |first1=Alistair |date=9 May 2013 |newspaper=[[Evening Standard]] |accessdate=18 May 2013}}</ref> but did not receive a second call from producer [[Harry Saltzman]] because, in Stamp's opinion, \"my ideas about [how the role should be portrayed] put the frighteners on Harry. I didn't get a second call from him.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Stamp: I blew my chance at Bond|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/news/stamp-i-blew-my-chance-at-bond-29256944.html |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=Belfast Telegraph}}</ref>\n\nStamp then travelled to Italy to star in [[Federico Fellini]]'s ''Toby Dammit'', a 50-minute portion of the [[Edgar Allan Poe]] film adaptation ''[[Histoires extraordinaires]]'' (1968, aka ''[[Spirits of the Dead]]''). Stamp lived in Italy for several years, during which time his film work included [[Pier Paolo Pasolini]]'s ''[[Teorema (film)|Teorema]]'' (1968) opposite [[Silvana Mangano]], and ''Una Stagione all'inferno'' (1970). Stamp was considered for the title role of ''[[Alfie (1966 film)|Alfie]]'' (1966), but turned it down in favour of ''[[Modesty Blaise (1966 film)|Modesty Blaise]]'' (1966).\n\nHis subsequent film credits included ''[[The Mind of Mr. Soames]]'' (1970), ''[[A Season in Hell]]'' (1971), ''[[Meetings with Remarkable Men (film)|Meetings with Remarkable Men]]'' (1979), and ''[[The Hit (1984 film)|The Hit]]'' (1984), which won a Mystfest Award for Best Actor, shared with [[John Hurt]] and [[Tim Roth]]. Also in 1984, he had the opportunity to play [[Satan|the Devil]] in a [[cameo appearance|cameo]] in ''[[The Company of Wolves]]''. He also appeared in ''[[Link (film)|Link]]'' (1986), ''[[Legal Eagles]]'' (1986), ''[[The Sicilian (film)|The Sicilian]]'' (1987), and a cameo as Sir Larry Wildman in ''[[Wall Street (1987 film)|Wall Street]]'' (1987). He played the ranch owner, John Tunstall, in ''[[Young Guns (film)|Young Guns]]'' (1988). His film ''[[Prince of Shadows|Beltenebros]]'' (1992) (aka ''Prince of Shadows''), was awarded the Silver Bear at the [[42nd Berlin International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Berlinale\">{{cite web |url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1992/03_preistr_ger_1992/03_Preistraeger_1992.html |title=Berlinale: 1992 Prize Winners |work=[[Berlin International Film Festival]] |accessdate=27 March 2011}}</ref> Stamp began his fourth decade as an actor wearing some of the choicest of Tim Chappel's Academy Award-winning costumes for the comedy ''[[The Adventures of Priscilla, Queen of the Desert]]'' (1994) which co-starred [[Guy Pearce]] and [[Hugo Weaving]].\n\nIn 1999, Stamp played a lead role in ''[[The Limey]]'' to widespread critical acclaim at the [[Cannes Film Festival]]. For his performance, Stamp received nominations for Best Male Lead at the 2000 [[Independent Spirit Awards]] and for Best British Actor at the [[London Film Critics' Circle|London Film Critics' Circle (ALFS) Awards]]. Also in 1999, Stamp appeared in the blockbuster ''[[Star Wars Episode&nbsp;I: The Phantom Menace]]'' as [[Chancellor Finis Valorum]] (an experience he later described as 'boring'),<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.indiewire.com/2013/01/terence-stamp-says-working-on-phantom-menace-was-boring-but-he-had-a-crush-on-natalie-portman-102011/ |title=Terence Stamp Says Working On 'Phantom Menace' Was \"Boring,\" But He Had A Crush On Natalie Portman |first=Joe |last=Cunningham |date=30 January 2013 |website=[[IndieWire]] |accessdate=11 February 2013}}</ref> followed by ''[[Bowfinger]]'' (1999) and ''[[Red Planet (film)|Red Planet]]'' (2000). He also appeared in [[Damian Pettigrew]]'s award-winning documentary, ''[[Fellini: I'm a Born Liar]]'' (2002), offering ideas into the mind and working methods of Italian director [[Federico Fellini]] with whom Stamp had worked in the 1960s.\n\n===''Superman'' roles===\n\n{{quote box|width=30%|bgcolor=#FFFFF0|align=right|quote=It was Stamp who transformed Superman's arch nemesis into a sadistic supervillain. The terrifying demand: 'Kneel before Zod!' is remembered as one of the most iconic moments in comic book film history.|source=\u2014Terence Stamp: five best moments \u2013 1. ''Superman II''. Article published in ''The Guardian'', February 2013.<ref name=\"Stamp best\">{{cite news |title=Terence Stamp: five best moments |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/filmblog/2013/feb/22/terence-stamp-five-best-moments |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=The Guardian}}</ref>}}\nStamp portrayed the [[Kryptonian]] supervillain [[General Zod]] in Richard Donner's ''[[Superman (1978 film)|Superman]]'' (1978), in which he appeared in a scene with [[Marlon Brando]]. The film and its first sequel were originally conceived as one film, with Zod and his evil conspirators returning later in the film to challenge Superman, but the screenplay was so long that the producers elected to split it into two parts. Both parts began shooting simultaneously, but production on the sequel was halted partway through due to budget and time constraints. Stamp reappeared as General Zod in the second part, ''[[Superman II]]'' (1980), as the movie's primary villain. Donner was replaced as director on the sequel with [[Richard Lester]], who completed the film using portions of Donner's original footage combined with newly filmed scenes. ''[[Total Film]]'' magazine ranked Stamp's portrayal of General Zod #32 on their \"Top 50 Greatest Villains of All Time\" list in 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://snarkerati.com/movie-news/the-top-50-greatest-heroes-villains-of-all-time-total-film-compiled-list/ |title=The Top 50 Greatest Heroes & Villains Of All Time - 'Total Film' Compiled List |website=Snarkerati.com |date=November 24, 2007 |accessdate=December 25, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130504151132/http://snarkerati.com/movie-news/the-top-50-greatest-heroes-villains-of-all-time-total-film-compiled-list/ |archivedate=May 4, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nOn the occasion of Superman's fiftieth anniversary in 1988, Stamp introduced the [[BBC Radio]] special ''[[Superman On Trial]]'', which was produced by [[Dirk Maggs]] and starred [[Stuart Milligan]] as Superman. In 2003, Stamp returned to the ''Superman'' franchise in a new role, by portraying the voice of [[Clark Kent (Smallville)|Clark Kent]]'s biological father [[Jor-El]] in the [[WB Television Network|WB]]/[[The CW Television Network|CW]] television series ''[[Smallville]]''. He also provided the scream of Zod (being exorcised from the body of [[Lex Luthor (Smallville)|Lex Luthor]]) in the sixth-season premiere episode \"Zod\". In 2006, he appeared as Zod once again in ''[[Superman II: The Richard Donner Cut]]'' (a retooled version of the 1980 film which features footage shot by Donner, the film's original director).\n\n===Recent years===\nIn recent years, Stamp has appeared in the films ''[[Ma femme est une actrice]]'' (aka ''My Wife Is An Actress'', 2001), ''[[My Boss's Daughter]]'' (2003), Disney's ''[[The Haunted Mansion (film)|The Haunted Mansion]]'' (2003), and the superhero fantasy ''[[Elektra (2005 film)|Elektra]]'' (2005). In 2008, he appeared in the film remake of the spy comedy ''[[Get Smart]]''; another comedy about the man who says yes to everything ''[[Yes Man (film)|Yes Man]]'', opposite [[Jim Carrey]]; with [[Angelina Jolie]], [[James McAvoy]] and [[Morgan Freeman]] in ''[[Wanted (2008 film)|Wanted]]''; and with [[Tom Cruise]] in ''[[Valkyrie (film)|Valkyrie]]'', based on the true story of Colonel [[Claus von Stauffenberg]]'s failed attempt to assassinate [[Adolf Hitler]].\n\nEntering in the 2010s, Stamp appeared in ''[[The Adjustment Bureau]]'' (2011), an American romantic science fiction thriller film loosely based on the [[Philip K. Dick]] short story, \"Adjustment Team\", opposite [[Matt Damon]]. In 2012, Stamp appeared in the [[Peter Serafinowicz]]-directed [[music video]] for the [[Hot Chip]] song \"Night & Day\",<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peterserafinowicz.com/night-and-day-directed-by-peter-serafinowicz |title=Night and Day \u2013 Directed by Peter Serafinowicz |website=PeterSerafinowicz.com |accessdate=21 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120523151149/http://www.peterserafinowicz.com/night-and-day-directed-by-peter-serafinowicz |archivedate=23 May 2012}}</ref> portrayed a grumpy husband called Arthur in [[Paul Andrew Williams]]' ''[[Song for Marion]]'' (2012),<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.mydesert.com/article/20130112/LIFESTYLES010201/301120065/Actor-Terence-Stamp-s-professional-spiritual-journey-led-him-an-Unfinished-Song-?nclick_check=1 |title=Actor Terence Stamp's professional and spiritual journey led him to an 'Unfinished Song' |first=Bruce |last=Fessier |date=13 January 2013 |work=[[The Desert Sun]] |accessdate=13 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130122185207/http://www.mydesert.com/article/20130112/LIFESTYLES010201/301120065/Actor-Terence-Stamp-s-professional-spiritual-journey-led-him-an-Unfinished-Song-?nclick_check=1 |archive-date=22 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.newsday.com/entertainment/movies/unfinished-song-review-vanessa-redgrave-terence-stamp-are-first-rate-1.5621551 |title='Unfinished Song' review: Vanessa Redgrave, Terence Stamp are first-rate |first=John |last=Anderson |work=[[Newsday]] |accessdate=3 July 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160609184010/http://www.newsday.com/entertainment/movies/unfinished-song-review-vanessa-redgrave-terence-stamp-are-first-rate-1.5621551 |archive-date=9 June 2016}}</ref> opposite [[Gemma Arterton]] and a heist comedy ''[[The Art of the Steal (2013 film)|The Art of the Steal]]'' (2013), with [[Kurt Russell]], [[Matt Dillon]] and [[Jay Baruchel]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/terrence-stamp-the-black-marks-283366 |title=Terence Stamp confirmed for the comedy The Black Marks |first=Borys |last=Kit |date=19 January 2012 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |accessdate=19 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Stamp appeared in [[Tim Burton]]'s drama film ''[[Big Eyes]]'', with [[Amy Adams]] and [[Christoph Waltz]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.screendaily.com/news/production/terence-stamp-joins-burtons-big-eyes/5057880.article |title=Terence Stamp joins Burton's Big Eyes |first=Wendy |last=Mitchell |date=29 June 2013 |work=Screen Daily |accessdate=29 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/terence-stamp-joins-tim-burtons-577277 |title=Terence Stamp Joins Tim Burton's 'Big Eyes' |first=Philiana |last=Ng |date=28 June 2013 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |accessdate=28 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/terence-stamp-joins-tim-burtons-big-eyes-plus-watch-40-minute-scene-by-scene-with-the-actor-20130702 |title=Terence Stamp Joins Tim Burton's 'Big Eyes' Plus Watch 40-Minute 'Scene By Scene' With The Actor |first=Ben |last=Brock |date=2 July 2013 |work=The Playlist |accessdate=2 July 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112230225/http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/terence-stamp-joins-tim-burtons-big-eyes-plus-watch-40-minute-scene-by-scene-with-the-actor-20130702 |archive-date=12 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.filmschoolrejects.com/news/casting-terence-stamp-rosemarie-dewitt.php |title=Casting Couch: Terence Stamp to Work With Tim Burton, Rosemarie Dewitt is Joining 'Kill the Messenger,' and More |first=Nathan |last=Adams |work=Film School Rejects |accessdate=1 July 2013}}</ref> In 2016, Stamp appeared in another Tim Burton film, ''[[Miss Peregrine's Home for Peculiar Children (film)|Miss Peregrine's Home for Peculiar Children]]'', where played Abe, the grandfather of the film's protagonist Jake.\n\nStamp's next project was ''[[Crooked House (film)|Crooked House]]'' (2017), directed by [[Gilles Paquet-Brenner]] and starring [[Christina Hendricks]], [[Gillian Anderson]] and [[Glenn Close]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.screendaily.com/5109411.article |title=Agatha Christie thriller 'Crooked House' underway |last=Wiseman |first=Andreas |date=13 September 2016 |website=Screen Daily |accessdate=14 September 2016}}</ref> He also appears in [[George Mendeluk]]'s ''[[Bitter Harvest (2017 film)|Bitter Harvest]]'', opposite [[Max Irons]], [[Samantha Barks]], [[Barry Pepper]], and [[Aneurin Barnard]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/10/aneurin-barnard-the-devils-harvest-book-of-life-channing-tatum-zoe-saldana/ |title=Aneurin Barnard Joins 'The Devil's Harvest'; Animated 'Book Of Life' Sets Channing Tatum, Zoe Saldana & More |first=Nancy |last=Tartaglione |date=16 October 2013 |work=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=17 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Books, music videos and voice acting ===\nIn addition to his acting career, Terence Stamp is an accomplished writer and author. He has published three volumes of his memoirs including ''Stamp Album'' (written in tribute to his late mother), a novel entitled ''The Night'', and a [[cookbook]] co-written with Elizabeth Buxton to provide alternative recipes for those who are [[gluten-related disorders|wheat]]- and [[Lactose intolerance|lactose-intolerant]]. Stamp's recent projects include the video game ''[[The Elder Scrolls&nbsp;IV: Oblivion]]'', in which he lends his voice to the villainous cult leader Mankar Camoran; and the films ''Zombie Island'' and ''[[These Foolish Things]]''. Stamp voiced the [[Prophet of Truth]] in ''[[Halo&nbsp;3]]'', replacing [[Michael Wincott]]. In 2005, Stamp also narrated the [[BBC Four]] [[documentary]] ''[[Jazz Britannia]]'', which chronicles the evolution of [[British jazz]] music.\n\nStamp read the book ''Perfect Brilliant Stillness'' by David Carse for SilkSoundBooks.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.silksoundbooks.com/authors/david-carse/perfect-brilliant-stillness.html |title=Perfect Brilliant Stillness Audio Book Download for your iPod |website=Silksoundbooks |date= |accessdate=23 January 2015}}</ref> In his introductory reading, Stamp describes his love for this book by saying, \"Greater love hath no man\". Stamp appeared in the music video for \"At the Bottom of Everything\" by [[Bright Eyes (band)|Bright Eyes]]. Stamp appeared as the featured 'castaway' on [[BBC Radio]]'s long-running ''[[Desert Island Discs]]'' in June 1987, and made a second appearance in March 2006 with a different selection of music.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/features/desert-island-discs/castaway/43f29962 |title=Desert Island Discs \u2013 Terence Stamp |website=BBC |accessdate=11 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002 Stamp provided the narration for ''History of Football: [[The Beautiful Game]]'', a series on all aspects of the world's most popular sport.<ref>{{cite book |last=Brown |first=David |date=2004 |title=God and Enchantment of Place: Reclaiming Human Experience |location=Oxford |publisher=Oxford University Press |page=398 |isbn=978-0-19927-198-6}}</ref> Stamp attended every [[England national football team|England]] game (including the [[1966 FIFA World Cup Final|final]]) at the [[1966 FIFA World Cup]], and in July 2016 he narrated ''1966 \u2013 A Nation Remembers'' shown on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]], marking the 50th anniversary of England's World Cup victory.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itv.com/presscentre/ep1week31/1966-nation-remembers |title=1966 \u2013 A Nation Remembers |date=5 October 2016 |website=ITV |access-date=1 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 July 2007, Stamp gave a speech on [[climate change]] at the [[Live Earth concert, London|British leg]] of [[Live Earth]] in [[Wembley Stadium]] before introducing [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]].<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/coffeehouse/2007/07/nobody-does-it-better/ |title=Nobody does it better |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=8 July 2007 |magazine=[[The Spectator]] |access-date=1 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|Xn0ym7RdN94|Video of speech}}</ref> His memoir, ''The Ocean Fell into the Drop'', was published by [[Repeater Books]] in 2017. Stamp also narrated the [[BBC]]'s ''The Story of [[Only Fools and Horses]]'' in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://repeaterbooks.com/books/the-ocean-fell-into-the-drop-by-terence-stamp/ |title=The Ocean Fell Into the Drop, by Terence Stamp |date=26 May 2017 |work=Repeater Books |access-date=27 October 2017 |language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Terence Stamp Allan Warren.jpg|thumb|Stamp in 1973, photographed by [[Allan Warren]]]]\nIn the 1960s, Stamp shared a house with actor [[Michael Caine]] in [[Wimpole Street]], London.<ref name=\"documentary\">''[[Let's Get Lost (1988 film)|Let's Get Lost]]'' (1988) documentary by [[Bruce Weber (photographer)|Bruce Weber]]</ref> before and during their rise to fame.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://eastlondonhistory.com/terence-stamps-london-roots/ |title=Terence Stamp's London roots |work=East London History |year=2011 |accessdate=26 November 2011}}</ref> In his autobiography, ''What's it All About'', Caine states that he \"still wakes up sweating in the night as he sees Terence agreeing to accept my advice to take the role in ''[[Alfie (play)|Alfie]]''\".\n\nStamp received extensive media coverage of his romances in the 1960s with film star [[Julie Christie]] and [[supermodel]] [[Jean Shrimpton]]. He and Shrimpton were one of the most-photographed couples of [[Swinging London|Mod London]]. It was after Shrimpton ended her relationship with Stamp that he moved to [[India]], spending time at the [[ashram]] of [[Jiddu Krishnamurti|Krishnamurti]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/mar/12/terence-stamp-i-was-in-my-prime-but-when-the-60s-ended-i-ended-with-it |title=Terence Stamp: 'I was in my prime, but when the 60s ended, I ended with it' |last=Pulver |first=Andrew |date=12 March 2015 |work=The Guardian |language=en |access-date=22 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/esmagazine/the-life-and-loves-of-terence-stamp-8588325.html |title=The life and loves of Terence Stamp |date=26 April 2013 |work=Evening Standard |access-date=22 July 2018 |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://www.amazon.com/Self-J-Krishnamurti-Terence-Stamp/dp/B00TI5HCBS |title=The Self |last=Krishnamurti |first=J. |access-date=22 July 2018}} Read By Terence Stamp.</ref>\n\nStamp's brother [[Chris Stamp|Chris]] became a [[rock music]] [[impresario]] credited with helping to bring [[The Who]] to prominence during the 1960s and co-founding [[Track Records]].\n\nIn 1984, English band [[The Smiths]] released their third single, \"[[What Difference Does It Make?]]\". The single cover was a photograph taken on the set of the film ''The Collector'' (but not depicted in the actual film). Originally, Stamp refused permission for the still to be used, and some pressings featured lead singer [[Morrissey]] in a re-enacted scene. In the re-enactment Morrissey is holding a glass of milk, as opposed to a [[chloroform]] pad in the original. Eventually, however, Stamp changed his mind, and the original cover was reinstated.\n\nOn New Year's Eve 2002, Stamp married for the first time at the age of 64. His 29-year-old bride was Elizabeth O'Rourke, whom Stamp first met in the mid-1990s at a [[pharmacy]] in [[Bondi, New South Wales|Bondi]], [[New South Wales]]. An Australian/[[Singaporean]] of [[Australia]]n and Indian-[[Singapore]]an parentage, O'Rourke was brought up in Singapore before moving to Australia in her early twenties to study [[pharmacology]]. The couple divorced on the grounds of his \"unreasonable behaviour\" in April 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7373801.stm |title=Actor Stamp and Wife Get Divorce |date=29 April 2008 |website=BBC News |accessdate=29 April 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1962\n| ''[[Billy Budd (film)|Billy Budd]]''\n| Billy Budd\n|[[Golden Globe Award for New Star of the Year - Actor]]<br />Nominated\u2014[[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]]<br />Nominated\u2014[[BAFTA Award for Best Newcomer]]\n|-\n| ''[[Term of Trial]]''\n| Mitchell\n|\n|-\n|1965\n| ''[[The Collector (1965 film)|The Collector]]''\n| Freddie Clegg\n| [[Best Actor Award (Cannes Film Festival)]]\n|-\n|1966\n| ''[[Modesty Blaise (1966 film)|Modesty Blaise]]''\n| [[Willie Garvin]]\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1967\n| ''[[Poor Cow]]''\n| Dave Fuller\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Far from the Madding Crowd (1967 film)|Far from the Madding Crowd]]''\n| Sgt. Francis 'Frank' Troy\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=3|1968\n| ''[[Blue (1968 film)|Blue]]''\n| Blue\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Spirits of the Dead]]''\n| Toby Dammit\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Teorema]]''\n| The Visitor\n|\n|-\n|1970\n| ''[[The Mind of Mr. Soames]]''\n| John Soames\n|\n|-\n|1971\n| ''[[A Season in Hell (1971 film)|A Season in Hell]]''\n| Arthur Rimbaud\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1975\n| ''[[The Divine Nymph]]''\n| Dany di Bagnasco\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Hu-man]]''\n| Terence\n|\n|-\n|1976\n| ''Striptease''\n| Alain\n|\n|-\n|1977\n| ''Black-Out''\n| Edgar Poe\n|\n|-\n|1978\n| ''[[Superman (1978 film)|Superman]]''\n| [[General Zod]]\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1979\n| ''[[Meetings with Remarkable Men (film)|Meetings with Remarkable Men]]''\n| Prince Lubovedsky\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Together?]]''\n| Henry\n|\n|-\n|1980\n| ''[[Superman II]]''\n| General Zod\n|\n|-\n|1981\n| ''[[Jules Verne's Mystery on Monster Island]]''\n| J.R. Taskinar/Skinner\n|\n|-\n|1982\n| ''[[Morte in Vaticano]]''\n| Padre Andreani, later Pope Giovanni Clemente I\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1984\n| ''[[The Hit (1984 film)|The Hit]]''\n| Willie Parker\n| Mystfest for Best Actor (Shared with [[John Hurt]] and [[Tim Roth]])\n|-\n| ''[[The Company of Wolves]]''\n| [[The Devil]]\n| Uncredited\n|-\n|rowspan=3|1986\n|''[[Legal Eagles]]''\n| Victor Taft\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Link (film)|Link]]''\n| Dr. Steven Phillip\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Hud (1986 film)|Hud]]''\n| Edward\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1987\n| ''[[The Sicilian (film)|The Sicilian]]''\n| Prince Borsa\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Wall Street (1987 film)|Wall Street]]''\n| Sir Larry Wildman\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1988\n|''[[Young Guns (film)|Young Guns]]''\n| [[John Tunstall]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Alien Nation (film)|Alien Nation]]''\n| William Harcourt\n|\n|-\n|1990\n| ''Genuine Risk''\n| Paul Hellwart\n|\n|-\n|1991\n| ''[[Prince of Shadows|Beltenebros]]''\n| Darman\n| [[Silver Bear for Best Actor]] at the [[42nd Berlin International Film Festival]]<ref name=\"Berlinale\" />\n|-\n|1993\n| ''[[The Real McCoy (film)|The Real McCoy]]''\n| Jack Schmidt\n|\n|-\n|1994\n| ''[[The Adventures of Priscilla, Queen of the Desert]]''\n| Bernadette Bassenger\n| [[Seattle International Film Festival|Seattle International Film Festival Award for Best Actor]]<br />Nominated\u2014[[Australian Film Institute Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role]]<br />Nominated\u2014[[BAFTA Award for Best Actor|BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role]]<br />Nominated\u2014[[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor - Motion Picture Musical or Comedy]]\n|-\n|1996\n| ''Limited Edition''\n| Edward Lamb\n| (''Tir\u00e9 \u00e0 Part'')\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1997\n| ''[[Love Walked In (1997 film)|Love Walked In]]''\n| Fred Moore\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Bliss (1997 film)|Bliss]]''\n| Baltazar\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=4|1999\n| ''[[The Limey]]''\n| Wilson\n| [[Satellite Award for Best Actor - Motion Picture Drama]]<br />Nominated\u2014[[Independent Spirit Award for Best Male Lead]]<br />Nominated\u2014Las Vegas Film Critics Society Award for Best Actor\n|-\n| ''[[Star Wars: Episode I \u2013 The Phantom Menace]]''\n| [[Supreme Chancellor Valorum|Supreme Chancellor Finis Valorum]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Bowfinger]]''\n| Terry Stricter\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Kiss the Sky (film)|Kiss the Sky]]''\n| Kozen\n|\n|-\n|2000\n| ''[[Red Planet (film)|Red Planet]]''\n| Dr. Bud Chantilas\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2001\n| ''[[Revelation (2001 film)|Revelation]]''\n| Magnus Martel\n|\n|-\n|''[[My Wife Is an Actress]]''\n| John\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2002\n| ''[[Full Frontal (film)|Full Frontal]]''\n| Man on Plane/Himself\n|\n|-\n|''[[Fellini: I'm a Born Liar]]''\n| Himself/Toby Dammit\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2003\n| ''[[My Boss's Daughter]]''\n| Jack Taylor\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Kiss (2003 film)|The Kiss]]''\n| Philip Naudet\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Haunted Mansion (film)|The Haunted Mansion]]''\n| Ramsley\n|\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Dead Fish]]''\n| Samuel Fish\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2005\n| ''[[Elektra (2005 film)|Elektra]]''\n| [[Stick (comics)|Stick]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[These Foolish Things (film)|These Foolish Things]]''\n| Baker\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2006\n| ''[[September Dawn]]''\n| [[Brigham Young]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Superman II: The Richard Donner Cut]]''\n| General Zod\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=5|2008\n| ''[[Wanted (2008 film)|Wanted]]''\n| Pekwarsky\n|\n|-\n| ''Flowers and Weeds''\n| Storyteller\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Get Smart (film)|Get Smart]]''\n| [[Get Smart#KAOS|Siegfried]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Yes Man (film)|Yes Man]]''\n| Terrence Bundley\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Valkyrie (film)|Valkyrie]]''\n| [[Ludwig Beck]]\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Ultramarines: A Warhammer 40,000 Movie]]''\n| Captain Severus\n| Voice Only\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[The Adjustment Bureau]]''\n| Thompson\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Song for Marion]]''\n| Arthur\n| [[Beijing International Film Festival]] for Best Actor <br /> Nominated\u2014[[BIFA Award for Best Performance by an Actor in a British Independent Film]]\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[The Art of the Steal (2013 film)|The Art of the Steal]]''\n| Samuel Winter\n|\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Big Eyes]]''\n| [[John Canaday]]\n| \n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Miss Peregrine's Home for Peculiar Children (film)|Miss Peregrine's Home for Peculiar Children]]''\n| Abraham \"Abe\" Portman\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2017\n| ''[[Crooked House (film)|Crooked House]]''\n| Chief Inspector Taverner\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Bitter Harvest (2017 film)|Bitter Harvest]]''\n| Ivan\n|\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Viking Destiny]]''\n| Odin\n| \n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Murder Mystery (film)|Murder Mystery]]''\n| Malcolm Quince\n| \n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Last Night in Soho]]''\n|\n| Post-production\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|1978\n| ''[[The Thief of Baghdad (1978 film)|The Thief of Baghdad]]''\n| Wazir Jaudur\n| Television film\n|-\n|1983\n| ''[[Chessgame]]''\n| David Audley\n| TV series\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1986\n| ''The Cold War Killers''\n| David Audley\n| Television film\n|-\n| ''[[The Hunger (serial)|The Hunger]]''\n| Host\n| TV series\n|-\n|2003\u20132011\n|''[[Smallville]]''\n| [[Jor-El]]\n|TV series, (Voice role only) <br/> 23 Episodes\n|-\n|2003\n| ''[[Static Shock]]''\n| Dennis/Professor Menace<ref name=\"btva\">{{cite web |url=https://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/Terence-Stamp/ |title=Behind The Voice Actors - Terence Stamp |website=Behind the Voice Actors |access-date=1 August 2019}}</ref>\n| TV series, ([[Voice acting|Voice role]] only) <br/> Episode: \"Blast from the Past\"\n|-\n|}\n\n===Video games===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|2006\n| ''[[The Elder Scrolls IV: Oblivion]]''\n| Mankar Camoran\n|\n|-\n|2007\n| ''[[Halo 3]]''\n| [[Prophet of Truth]]<ref name=\"btva\"/>\n|\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[Wanted: Weapons of Fate]]''\n|Pekwarsky\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n==Awards==\nStamp found success with his first film ''[[Billy Budd (film)|Billy Budd]]'' (1962), for which he won the [[Golden Globe Award for New Star of the Year - Actor]] and was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]] and the [[BAFTA Award for Best Newcomer]]. Stamp also won early recognition for the film ''[[The Collector (1965 film)|The Collector]]'' (1965); for this, he won the [[Cannes Film Festival Award for Best Actor]].\n\nFor ''[[The Adventures of Priscilla, Queen of the Desert]]'' (1994), Stamp won the [[Seattle International Film Festival|Seattle International Film Festival for Best Actor]] and was nominated for the [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role]] and the [[Australian Film Institute Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role]]. For ''[[The Limey]]'' (1999), he won the [[Satellite Award for Best Actor - Motion Picture| Satellite Award for Best Actor - Motion Picture Drama]] and was nominated for the [[Independent Spirit Award for Best Male Lead]].\n\nStamp was nominated for the [[BIFA Award for Best Performance by an Actor in a British Independent Film]] for ''[[Song for Marion]]'' (2012).\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n\n===Won===\n'''Golden Globe'''\n*[[Golden Globe Award for New Star of the Year - Actor|New Star of the Year \u2013 Actor]] \u2013 ''[[Billy Budd (film)|Billy Budd]]'' (1962)\n\n'''Cannes Film Festival'''\n*[[Best Actor Award (Cannes Film Festival)|Best Actor Award]] \u2013 ''[[The Collector (1965 film)|The Collector]]'' (1965)\n\n'''Mystfest'''\n*Best Actor \u2013 ''[[The Hit (1984 film)|The Hit]]'' (1984)\n\n'''Seattle International Film Festival'''\n*[[Seattle International Film Festival|Best Actor]] \u2013 ''[[The Adventures of Priscilla, Queen of the Desert]]'' (1994)\n\n'''Satellite Award'''\n*[[Satellite Award for Best Actor - Motion Picture Drama|Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Drama]] \u2013 ''[[The Limey]]'' (1999)\n*Outstanding Contribution to the Entertainment Industry ([[Satellite Awards 2012|2012]])\n\n'''Silver Bear'''\n*[[Silver Bear for Best Actor|Best Actor]] \u2013 ''[[Prince of Shadows|Beltenebros]]'' (1991)\n\n''' Beijing International Film Festival Tian Tan Award'''\n*[[Beijing International Film Festival|Best Actor]] \u2013 ''[[Song for Marion]]'' (2012)\n\n{{col-break}}\n\n===Nominated===\n'''Academy Award'''\n*[[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] \u2013 ''[[Billy Budd (film)|Billy Budd]]'' (1962)\n\n'''British Independent Film Awards'''\n*[[BIFA Award for Best Performance by an Actor in a British Independent Film|Best Actor]]\u2014''[[Song for Marion]]'' (2012)\n\n'''Golden Globe'''\n*[[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor - Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy]] \u2013 ''[[The Adventures of Priscilla, Queen of the Desert]]'' (1994)\n\n'''BAFTA Award'''\n*[[BAFTA Award for Best Newcomer|Best Newcomer]] \u2013 ''Billy Budd'' (1962)\n*[[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role|Best Actor in a Leading Role]] \u2013 ''The Adventures of Priscilla, Queen of the Desert'' (1994)\n\n'''Australian Film Institute Award'''\n*[[Australian Film Institute Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role|Best Actor in a Leading Role]] \u2013 ''The Adventures of Priscilla, Queen of the Desert'' (1994)\n\n'''Independent Spirit Award'''\n*[[Independent Spirit Award for Best Male Lead|Best Male Lead]] \u2013 ''[[The Limey]]'' (1999)\n\n'''Las Vegas Film Critics Society Award'''\n*Best Actor \u2013 ''The Limey'' (1999)<ref name=\"StampAlbum\"/>\n{{col-end}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal bar|Biography}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Terence Stamp}}\n* {{IMDb name|0000654}}\n* {{Screenonline name|id=453285}}\n* {{amg name|67541}}\n* {{Tcmdb name}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box\n|title=Actors portraying [[General Zod]]\n|years=1978\u20131980<br />for ''[[Superman (1978 film)|Superman]]'' and ''[[Superman II]]''\n|before=N/A\n|after=[[Callum Blue]]<br />2003\u20132011<br />'''for ''[[Smallville]]'' '''\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Terence Stamp\n|list =\n{{Prix d'interpr\u00e9tation masculine 1960\u20131979}}\n{{Golden Globe Award for New Star of the Year Actor}}\n{{Satellite Award Best Actor Motion Picture}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stamp, Terence}}\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Webber Douglas Academy of Dramatic Art]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:Cannes Film Festival Award for Best Actor winners]]\n[[Category:Independent Spirit Award winners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Star of the Year (Actor) Golden Globe winners]]\n[[Category:People from Stepney]]\n[[Category:Silver Bear for Best Actor winners]]\n[[Category:Male actors from London]]\n[[Category:Rajneesh movement]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British actor}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2010}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Terence Stamp\n| image = Terence Stamp.2794.jpg\n| caption = Stamp at the [[Valkyrie (film)|Valkyrie]] premiere in Berlin, 2009\n| birth_name = Terence Henry Stamp\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1938|7|22|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Stepney]], [[London]], England\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| occupation = Actor\n| years_active = 1962\u2013present\n| spouse = {{marriage|Elizabeth O'Rourke|2002|2008|reason=divorced}}\n| relatives = [[Chris Stamp]] (brother; deceased)\n}}\n\n'''Terence Henry Stamp''' (born 22 July 1938)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=BRGIjhAqTGTw%2FEId%2FJFxkg&scan=1 |title=Index entry |work=[[FreeBMD]] |publisher=ONS |accessdate=15 February 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"filmr\">{{cite web |url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/99/Terence-Stamp.html |title=Terence Stamp Biography (1938?-) |website=FilmReference.com |date= |accessdate=30 September 2010}}</ref> is an English actor. After training at the [[Webber Douglas Academy of Dramatic Art]] in London he started his acting career in 1962. Regarded as a \u201cmaster of the brooding silence\u201d by ''The Guardian'', Stamp has appeared in more than 60 films.<ref name=\u201cStamp best\u201d/> His performance in the title role of ''[[Billy Budd (film)|Billy Budd]]'', his film debut, earned him an [[Academy Award]] nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] and a [[BAFTA Award|BAFTA]] nomination for [[BAFTA Award for Best Newcomer|Best Newcomer]]. Associated with the [[swinging London]] scene of the 1960s \u2013 during which time he was in a high-profile relationship with [[Julie Christie]] \u2013 Stamp was among the subjects photographed by [[David Bailey]] for a set titled ''Box of Pin-Ups''.<ref>{{cite book |first=Christopher |last=Bray |title=1965: The Year Modern Britain was Born |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8XwyAQAAQBAJ&pg=PT195 |year=2014 |publisher=Simon & Schuster |location=London |page=xii |isbn=978-1-84983-387-5}}</ref>\n\nStamp played butterfly collector Freddie Clegg in ''[[The Collector (1965 film)|The Collector]]'' (1965), and in 1967 appeared in ''[[Far from the Madding Crowd (1967 film)|Far from the Madding Crowd]]'', starring opposite Christie. His other major roles include playing archvillain [[General Zod]] in ''[[Superman (1978 film)|Superman]]'' and ''[[Superman II]]'', tough guy Wilson in ''[[The Limey]]'', [[Supreme Chancellor Valorum]] in ''[[Star Wars: Episode I \u2013 The Phantom Menace]]'', transgender woman Bernadette Bassinger in ''[[The Adventures of Priscilla, Queen of the Desert]]'', ghost antagonist Ramsley in ''[[The Haunted Mansion (film)|The Haunted Mansion]]'', [[Stick (comics)|Stick]] in ''[[Elektra (2005 film)|Elektra]]'', Pekwarsky in ''[[Wanted (2008 film)|Wanted]]'', Siegfried in ''[[Get Smart (film)|Get Smart]]'', Terrence Bundley in ''[[Yes Man (film)|Yes Man]]'', the Prophet of Truth in ''[[Halo 3]]'', Mankar Camoran in ''[[The Elder Scrolls IV: Oblivion]]'', and General [[Ludwig Beck]] in ''[[Valkyrie (film)|Valkyrie]]''. He has appeared in [[List of frequent Tim Burton collaborators|two Tim Burton films]], ''[[Big Eyes]]'' (2014) and ''[[Miss Peregrine's Home for Peculiar Children (film)|Miss Peregrine's Home for Peculiar Children]]'' (2016).\n\nFor his acting, Stamp has won a [[Golden Globe]], a Mystfest, a [[Cannes Film Festival]] Award, a [[Seattle International Film Festival]] Award, a [[Satellite Award]], and a [[Silver Bear]]. Stamp has also had voice work, narrating ''[[Jazz Britannia]]'' on the [[BBC]], and ''1966 \u2013 A Nation Remembers'' on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] in July 2016 which marked the 50th anniversary of England's [[1966 FIFA World Cup]] victory.\n\n==Early life==\nStamp, the eldest of five children, was born in [[Stepney]], [[London]], England, the son of Ethel Esther (n\u00e9e Perrott; 1914\u20131987) and Thomas Stamp (1912\u20131982), who was a [[tugboat]] stoker.<ref name=\"filmr\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/contributor/1800014689/bio |title=Terence Stamp Biography |website=Yahoo! Movies |date= |accessdate=30 September 2010}}</ref> His early years were spent in Canal Road, [[Bow, London|Bow]],<ref>Internet Movie Database.</ref> in the [[East End of London|East End]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://observer.guardian.co.uk/foodmonthly/story/0,,662828,00.html |title=Mr Intolerant |first=Caroline |last=Boucher |date=10 March 2002 |work=[[The Observer]] |location=London |accessdate=25 May 2010}}</ref> but later in his childhood the family moved to [[Plaistow, Newham|Plaistow]], [[County Borough of West Ham|West Ham]], [[Essex]] (now in [[Greater London]]), where he attended [[Plaistow County Grammar School]]. His father was away for long periods with the [[British Merchant Navy|Merchant Navy]] and the young Stamp was mostly brought up by his mother, grandmother, and aunts. He grew up idolising actor [[Gary Cooper]] after his mother took him to see ''[[Beau Geste (1939 film)|Beau Geste]]'' (1939) when he was three years old. He was also inspired by the 1950s [[Method acting|method-trained]] actor [[James Dean]].\n\nAfter leaving school, Stamp worked in a variety of [[Advertising agency|advertising agencies]] in London, working his way up to earning a reasonable salary. In the mid\u20111950s, he also worked as an assistant to professional golfer Reg Knight at [[Wanstead]] Golf Club in [[east London]]. He describes this period of his life positively in his autobiography ''Stamp Album''.<ref name=\"StampAlbum\">{{cite book |last=Stamp |first=Terence |date=1987 |title=Stamp Album |location=London |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing |isbn=978-0-74750-032-2}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n=== Early career and rise to fame ===\nStamp won a [[scholarship]] to train at the [[Webber Douglas Academy of Dramatic Art]], then performed in various provincial [[repertory theatre]]s,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://escargotbooksonline.com/author_terence_stamp_ebook.php |title=Terence Stamp Biography |work=Escargot Books |year=2011 |accessdate=26 November 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120120101002/http://escargotbooksonline.com/author_terence_stamp_ebook.php |archivedate=20 January 2012}}</ref> most notably in a national tour of [[Willis Hall]]'s play ''[[The Long and the Short and the Tall (play)|The Long the Short and the Tall]]'' alongside another young cockney actor [[Michael Caine]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.silksoundbooks.com/performers/terence-stamp/ |title=Terence Stamp reads audio books |work=Silk Sound Books |year=2011 |accessdate=26 November 2011}}</ref> Caine moved in with Stamp, and they began hanging out with [[Peter O'Toole]] in the London party scene.<ref name=\"Caine 2019\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.ie/entertainment/movies/michael-caine-tales-of-a-jobbing-cockney-34385708.html |title=Michael Caine: Tales of a jobbing cockney |date=24 January 2016 |newspaper=[[Irish Independent]] |access-date=7 February 2019}}</ref> Stamp made his film debut in [[Peter Ustinov]]'s film adaptation of [[Herman Melville]]'s ''[[Billy Budd (film)|Billy Budd]]'' (1962). His portrayal of the title character brought him not only an [[Academy Award]] nomination but also international attention. He then appeared opposite [[Laurence Olivier]] in ''[[Term of Trial]]'' (1962).\n[[File:Monica Vitti en Terence Stamp (1965).jpg|thumb|right|Stamp with actress [[Monica Vitti]] in 1965 during filming ''[[Modesty Blaise (1966 film)|Modesty Blaise]]'']] \nStamp collaborated with some of the most revered filmmakers. He starred in [[William Wyler]]'s adaptation of [[John Fowles]]' ''[[The Collector]]'' (1965), opposite [[Samantha Eggar]], and in ''[[Modesty Blaise (1966 film)|Modesty Blaise]]'' (1966), for director [[Joseph Losey]] and producer Joe Janni. Stamp reunited with producer Janni for two more projects: [[John Schlesinger]]'s adaptation of [[Thomas Hardy]]'s ''[[Far from the Madding Crowd (1967 film)|Far from the Madding Crowd]]'' (1967) starring [[Julie Christie]], and [[Ken Loach]]'s first feature film ''[[Poor Cow]]'' (1967).\n\nHe was approached to play the role of [[James Bond]] when [[Sean Connery]] retired from the role,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/showbiz/celebrity-news/terence-stamp-i-blew-the-chance-to-play-james-bond-8608829.html |title=Terence Stamp: I blew the chance to play James Bond |last1=Foster |first1=Alistair |date=9 May 2013 |newspaper=[[Evening Standard]] |accessdate=18 May 2013}}</ref> but did not receive a second call from producer [[Harry Saltzman]] because, in Stamp's opinion, \"my ideas about [how the role should be portrayed] put the frighteners on Harry. I didn't get a second call from him.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Stamp: I blew my chance at Bond|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/news/stamp-i-blew-my-chance-at-bond-29256944.html |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=Belfast Telegraph}}</ref>\n\nStamp then travelled to Italy to star in [[Federico Fellini]]'s ''Toby Dammit'', a 50-minute portion of the [[Edgar Allan Poe]] film adaptation ''[[Histoires extraordinaires]]'' (1968, aka ''[[Spirits of the Dead]]''). Stamp lived in Italy for several years, during which time his film work included [[Pier Paolo Pasolini]]'s ''[[Teorema (film)|Teorema]]'' (1968) opposite [[Silvana Mangano]], and ''Una Stagione all'inferno'' (1970). Stamp was considered for the title role of ''[[Alfie (1966 film)|Alfie]]'' (1966), but turned it down in favour of ''[[Modesty Blaise (1966 film)|Modesty Blaise]]'' (1966).\n\nHis subsequent film credits included ''[[The Mind of Mr. Soames]]'' (1970), ''[[A Season in Hell]]'' (1971), ''[[Meetings with Remarkable Men (film)|Meetings with Remarkable Men]]'' (1979), and ''[[The Hit (1984 film)|The Hit]]'' (1984), which won a Mystfest Award for Best Actor, shared with [[John Hurt]] and [[Tim Roth]]. Also in 1984, he had the opportunity to play [[Satan|the Devil]] in a [[cameo appearance|cameo]] in ''[[The Company of Wolves]]''. He also appeared in ''[[Link (film)|Link]]'' (1986), ''[[Legal Eagles]]'' (1986), ''[[The Sicilian (film)|The Sicilian]]'' (1987), and a cameo as Sir Larry Wildman in ''[[Wall Street (1987 film)|Wall Street]]'' (1987). He played the ranch owner, John Tunstall, in ''[[Young Guns (film)|Young Guns]]'' (1988). His film ''[[Prince of Shadows|Beltenebros]]'' (1992) (aka ''Prince of Shadows''), was awarded the Silver Bear at the [[42nd Berlin International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Berlinale\">{{cite web |url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1992/03_preistr_ger_1992/03_Preistraeger_1992.html |title=Berlinale: 1992 Prize Winners |work=[[Berlin International Film Festival]] |accessdate=27 March 2011}}</ref> Stamp began his fourth decade as an actor wearing some of the choicest of Tim Chappel's Academy Award-winning costumes for the comedy ''[[The Adventures of Priscilla, Queen of the Desert]]'' (1994) which co-starred [[Guy Pearce]] and [[Hugo Weaving]].\n\nIn 1999, Stamp played a lead role in ''[[The Limey]]'' to widespread critical acclaim at the [[Cannes Film Festival]]. For his performance, Stamp received nominations for Best Male Lead at the 2000 [[Independent Spirit Awards]] and for Best British Actor at the [[London Film Critics' Circle|London Film Critics' Circle (ALFS) Awards]]. Also in 1999, Stamp appeared in the blockbuster ''[[Star Wars Episode&nbsp;I: The Phantom Menace]]'' as [[Chancellor Finis Valorum]] (an experience he later described as 'boring'),<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.indiewire.com/2013/01/terence-stamp-says-working-on-phantom-menace-was-boring-but-he-had-a-crush-on-natalie-portman-102011/ |title=Terence Stamp Says Working On 'Phantom Menace' Was \"Boring,\" But He Had A Crush On Natalie Portman |first=Joe |last=Cunningham |date=30 January 2013 |website=[[IndieWire]] |accessdate=11 February 2013}}</ref> followed by ''[[Bowfinger]]'' (1999) and ''[[Red Planet (film)|Red Planet]]'' (2000). He also appeared in [[Damian Pettigrew]]'s award-winning documentary, ''[[Fellini: I'm a Born Liar]]'' (2002), offering ideas into the mind and working methods of Italian director [[Federico Fellini]] with whom Stamp had worked in the 1960s.\n\n===''Superman'' roles===\n\n{{quote box|width=30%|bgcolor=#FFFFF0|align=right|quote=It was Stamp who transformed Superman's arch nemesis into a sadistic supervillain. The terrifying demand: 'Kneel before Zod!' is remembered as one of the most iconic moments in comic book film history.|source=\u2014Terence Stamp: five best moments \u2013 1. ''Superman II''. Article published in ''The Guardian'', February 2013.<ref name=\u201cStamp best\u201d>{{cite news |title=Terence Stamp: five best moments |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/filmblog/2013/feb/22/terence-stamp-five-best-moments |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=The Guardian}}</ref>}}\nStamp portrayed the [[Kryptonian]] supervillain [[General Zod]] in Richard Donner's ''[[Superman (1978 film)|Superman]]'' (1978), in which he appeared in a scene with [[Marlon Brando]]. The film and its first sequel were originally conceived as one film, with Zod and his evil conspirators returning later in the film to challenge Superman, but the screenplay was so long that the producers elected to split it into two parts. Both parts began shooting simultaneously, but production on the sequel was halted partway through due to budget and time constraints. Stamp reappeared as General Zod in the second part, ''[[Superman II]]'' (1980), as the movie's primary villain. Donner was replaced as director on the sequel with [[Richard Lester]], who completed the film using portions of Donner's original footage combined with newly filmed scenes. ''[[Total Film]]'' magazine ranked Stamp's portrayal of General Zod #32 on their \"Top 50 Greatest Villains of All Time\" list in 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://snarkerati.com/movie-news/the-top-50-greatest-heroes-villains-of-all-time-total-film-compiled-list/ |title=The Top 50 Greatest Heroes & Villains Of All Time - 'Total Film' Compiled List |website=Snarkerati.com |date=November 24, 2007 |accessdate=December 25, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130504151132/http://snarkerati.com/movie-news/the-top-50-greatest-heroes-villains-of-all-time-total-film-compiled-list/ |archivedate=May 4, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nOn the occasion of Superman's fiftieth anniversary in 1988, Stamp introduced the [[BBC Radio]] special ''[[Superman On Trial]]'', which was produced by [[Dirk Maggs]] and starred [[Stuart Milligan]] as Superman. In 2003, Stamp returned to the ''Superman'' franchise in a new role, by portraying the voice of [[Clark Kent (Smallville)|Clark Kent]]'s biological father [[Jor-El]] in the [[WB Television Network|WB]]/[[The CW Television Network|CW]] television series ''[[Smallville]]''. He also provided the scream of Zod (being exorcised from the body of [[Lex Luthor (Smallville)|Lex Luthor]]) in the sixth-season premiere episode \"Zod\". In 2006, he appeared as Zod once again in ''[[Superman II: The Richard Donner Cut]]'' (a retooled version of the 1980 film which features footage shot by Donner, the film's original director).\n\n===Recent years===\nIn recent years, Stamp has appeared in the films ''[[Ma femme est une actrice]]'' (aka ''My Wife Is An Actress'', 2001), ''[[My Boss's Daughter]]'' (2003), Disney's ''[[The Haunted Mansion (film)|The Haunted Mansion]]'' (2003), and the superhero fantasy ''[[Elektra (2005 film)|Elektra]]'' (2005). In 2008, he appeared in the film remake of the spy comedy ''[[Get Smart]]''; another comedy about the man who says yes to everything ''[[Yes Man (film)|Yes Man]]'', opposite [[Jim Carrey]]; with [[Angelina Jolie]], [[James McAvoy]] and [[Morgan Freeman]] in ''[[Wanted (2008 film)|Wanted]]''; and with [[Tom Cruise]] in ''[[Valkyrie (film)|Valkyrie]]'', based on the true story of Colonel [[Claus von Stauffenberg]]'s failed attempt to assassinate [[Adolf Hitler]].\n\nEntering in the 2010s, Stamp appeared in ''[[The Adjustment Bureau]]'' (2011), an American romantic science fiction thriller film loosely based on the [[Philip K. Dick]] short story, \"Adjustment Team\", opposite [[Matt Damon]]. In 2012, Stamp appeared in the [[Peter Serafinowicz]]-directed [[music video]] for the [[Hot Chip]] song \"Night & Day\",<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peterserafinowicz.com/night-and-day-directed-by-peter-serafinowicz |title=Night and Day \u2013 Directed by Peter Serafinowicz |website=PeterSerafinowicz.com |accessdate=21 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120523151149/http://www.peterserafinowicz.com/night-and-day-directed-by-peter-serafinowicz |archivedate=23 May 2012}}</ref> portrayed a grumpy husband called Arthur in [[Paul Andrew Williams]]' ''[[Song for Marion]]'' (2012),<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.mydesert.com/article/20130112/LIFESTYLES010201/301120065/Actor-Terence-Stamp-s-professional-spiritual-journey-led-him-an-Unfinished-Song-?nclick_check=1 |title=Actor Terence Stamp's professional and spiritual journey led him to an 'Unfinished Song' |first=Bruce |last=Fessier |date=13 January 2013 |work=[[The Desert Sun]] |accessdate=13 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130122185207/http://www.mydesert.com/article/20130112/LIFESTYLES010201/301120065/Actor-Terence-Stamp-s-professional-spiritual-journey-led-him-an-Unfinished-Song-?nclick_check=1 |archive-date=22 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.newsday.com/entertainment/movies/unfinished-song-review-vanessa-redgrave-terence-stamp-are-first-rate-1.5621551 |title='Unfinished Song' review: Vanessa Redgrave, Terence Stamp are first-rate |first=John |last=Anderson |work=[[Newsday]] |accessdate=3 July 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160609184010/http://www.newsday.com/entertainment/movies/unfinished-song-review-vanessa-redgrave-terence-stamp-are-first-rate-1.5621551 |archive-date=9 June 2016}}</ref> opposite [[Gemma Arterton]] and a heist comedy ''[[The Art of the Steal (2013 film)|The Art of the Steal]]'' (2013), with [[Kurt Russell]], [[Matt Dillon]] and [[Jay Baruchel]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/terrence-stamp-the-black-marks-283366 |title=Terence Stamp confirmed for the comedy The Black Marks |first=Borys |last=Kit |date=19 January 2012 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |accessdate=19 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Stamp appeared in [[Tim Burton]]'s drama film ''[[Big Eyes]]'', with [[Amy Adams]] and [[Christoph Waltz]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.screendaily.com/news/production/terence-stamp-joins-burtons-big-eyes/5057880.article |title=Terence Stamp joins Burton's Big Eyes |first=Wendy |last=Mitchell |date=29 June 2013 |work=Screen Daily |accessdate=29 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/terence-stamp-joins-tim-burtons-577277 |title=Terence Stamp Joins Tim Burton's 'Big Eyes' |first=Philiana |last=Ng |date=28 June 2013 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |accessdate=28 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/terence-stamp-joins-tim-burtons-big-eyes-plus-watch-40-minute-scene-by-scene-with-the-actor-20130702 |title=Terence Stamp Joins Tim Burton's 'Big Eyes' Plus Watch 40-Minute 'Scene By Scene' With The Actor |first=Ben |last=Brock |date=2 July 2013 |work=The Playlist |accessdate=2 July 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112230225/http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/terence-stamp-joins-tim-burtons-big-eyes-plus-watch-40-minute-scene-by-scene-with-the-actor-20130702 |archive-date=12 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.filmschoolrejects.com/news/casting-terence-stamp-rosemarie-dewitt.php |title=Casting Couch: Terence Stamp to Work With Tim Burton, Rosemarie Dewitt is Joining 'Kill the Messenger,' and More |first=Nathan |last=Adams |work=Film School Rejects |accessdate=1 July 2013}}</ref> In 2016, Stamp appeared in another Tim Burton film, ''[[Miss Peregrine's Home for Peculiar Children (film)|Miss Peregrine's Home for Peculiar Children]]'', where played Abe, the grandfather of the film's protagonist Jake.\n\nStamp's next project was ''[[Crooked House (film)|Crooked House]]'' (2017), directed by [[Gilles Paquet-Brenner]] and starring [[Christina Hendricks]], [[Gillian Anderson]] and [[Glenn Close]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.screendaily.com/5109411.article |title=Agatha Christie thriller 'Crooked House' underway |last=Wiseman |first=Andreas |date=13 September 2016 |website=Screen Daily |accessdate=14 September 2016}}</ref> He also appears in [[George Mendeluk]]'s ''[[Bitter Harvest (2017 film)|Bitter Harvest]]'', opposite [[Max Irons]], [[Samantha Barks]], [[Barry Pepper]], and [[Aneurin Barnard]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/10/aneurin-barnard-the-devils-harvest-book-of-life-channing-tatum-zoe-saldana/ |title=Aneurin Barnard Joins 'The Devil's Harvest'; Animated 'Book Of Life' Sets Channing Tatum, Zoe Saldana & More |first=Nancy |last=Tartaglione |date=16 October 2013 |work=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=17 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Books, music videos and voice acting ===\nIn addition to his acting career, Terence Stamp is an accomplished writer and author. He has published three volumes of his memoirs including ''Stamp Album'' (written in tribute to his late mother), a novel entitled ''The Night'', and a [[cookbook]] co-written with Elizabeth Buxton to provide alternative recipes for those who are [[gluten-related disorders|wheat]]- and [[Lactose intolerance|lactose-intolerant]]. Stamp's recent projects include the video game ''[[The Elder Scrolls&nbsp;IV: Oblivion]]'', in which he lends his voice to the villainous cult leader Mankar Camoran; and the films ''Zombie Island'' and ''[[These Foolish Things]]''. Stamp voiced the [[Prophet of Truth]] in ''[[Halo&nbsp;3]]'', replacing [[Michael Wincott]]. In 2005, Stamp also narrated the [[BBC Four]] [[documentary]] ''[[Jazz Britannia]]'', which chronicles the evolution of [[British jazz]] music.\n\nStamp read the book ''Perfect Brilliant Stillness'' by David Carse for SilkSoundBooks.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.silksoundbooks.com/authors/david-carse/perfect-brilliant-stillness.html |title=Perfect Brilliant Stillness Audio Book Download for your iPod |website=Silksoundbooks |date= |accessdate=23 January 2015}}</ref> In his introductory reading, Stamp describes his love for this book by saying, \"Greater love hath no man\". Stamp appeared in the music video for \"At the Bottom of Everything\" by [[Bright Eyes (band)|Bright Eyes]]. Stamp appeared as the featured 'castaway' on [[BBC Radio]]'s long-running ''[[Desert Island Discs]]'' in June 1987, and made a second appearance in March 2006 with a different selection of music.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/features/desert-island-discs/castaway/43f29962 |title=Desert Island Discs \u2013 Terence Stamp |website=BBC |accessdate=11 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002 Stamp provided the narration for ''History of Football: [[The Beautiful Game]]'', a series on all aspects of the world's most popular sport.<ref>{{cite book |last=Brown |first=David |date=2004 |title=God and Enchantment of Place: Reclaiming Human Experience |location=Oxford |publisher=Oxford University Press |page=398 |isbn=978-0-19927-198-6}}</ref> Stamp attended every [[England national football team|England]] game (including the [[1966 FIFA World Cup Final|final]]) at the [[1966 FIFA World Cup]], and in July 2016 he narrated ''1966 \u2013 A Nation Remembers'' shown on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]], marking the 50th anniversary of England's World Cup victory.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itv.com/presscentre/ep1week31/1966-nation-remembers |title=1966 \u2013 A Nation Remembers |date=5 October 2016 |website=ITV |access-date=1 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 July 2007, Stamp gave a speech on [[climate change]] at the [[Live Earth concert, London|British leg]] of [[Live Earth]] in [[Wembley Stadium]] before introducing [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]].<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/coffeehouse/2007/07/nobody-does-it-better/ |title=Nobody does it better |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=8 July 2007 |magazine=[[The Spectator]] |access-date=1 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|Xn0ym7RdN94|Video of speech}}</ref> His memoir, ''The Ocean Fell into the Drop'', was published by [[Repeater Books]] in 2017. Stamp also narrated the [[BBC]]'s ''The Story of [[Only Fools and Horses]]'' in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://repeaterbooks.com/books/the-ocean-fell-into-the-drop-by-terence-stamp/ |title=The Ocean Fell Into the Drop, by Terence Stamp |date=26 May 2017 |work=Repeater Books |access-date=27 October 2017 |language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Terence Stamp Allan Warren.jpg|thumb|Stamp in 1973, photographed by [[Allan Warren]]]]\nIn the 1960s, Stamp shared a house with actor [[Michael Caine]] in [[Wimpole Street]], London.<ref name=\"documentary\">''[[Let's Get Lost (1988 film)|Let's Get Lost]]'' (1988) documentary by [[Bruce Weber (photographer)|Bruce Weber]]</ref> before and during their rise to fame.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://eastlondonhistory.com/terence-stamps-london-roots/ |title=Terence Stamp's London roots |work=East London History |year=2011 |accessdate=26 November 2011}}</ref> In his autobiography, ''What's it All About'', Caine states that he \"still wakes up sweating in the night as he sees Terence agreeing to accept my advice to take the role in ''[[Alfie (play)|Alfie]]''\".\n\nStamp received extensive media coverage of his romances in the 1960s with film star [[Julie Christie]] and [[supermodel]] [[Jean Shrimpton]]. He and Shrimpton were one of the most-photographed couples of [[Swinging London|Mod London]]. It was after Shrimpton ended her relationship with Stamp that he moved to [[India]], spending time at the [[ashram]] of [[Jiddu Krishnamurti|Krishnamurti]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/mar/12/terence-stamp-i-was-in-my-prime-but-when-the-60s-ended-i-ended-with-it |title=Terence Stamp: 'I was in my prime, but when the 60s ended, I ended with it' |last=Pulver |first=Andrew |date=12 March 2015 |work=The Guardian |language=en |access-date=22 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/esmagazine/the-life-and-loves-of-terence-stamp-8588325.html |title=The life and loves of Terence Stamp |date=26 April 2013 |work=Evening Standard |access-date=22 July 2018 |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://www.amazon.com/Self-J-Krishnamurti-Terence-Stamp/dp/B00TI5HCBS |title=The Self |last=Krishnamurti |first=J. |access-date=22 July 2018}} Read By Terence Stamp.</ref>\n\nStamp's brother [[Chris Stamp|Chris]] became a [[rock music]] [[impresario]] credited with helping to bring [[The Who]] to prominence during the 1960s and co-founding [[Track Records]].\n\nIn 1984, English band [[The Smiths]] released their third single, \"[[What Difference Does It Make?]]\". The single cover was a photograph taken on the set of the film ''The Collector'' (but not depicted in the actual film). Originally, Stamp refused permission for the still to be used, and some pressings featured lead singer [[Morrissey]] in a re-enacted scene. In the re-enactment Morrissey is holding a glass of milk, as opposed to a [[chloroform]] pad in the original. Eventually, however, Stamp changed his mind, and the original cover was reinstated.\n\nOn New Year's Eve 2002, Stamp married for the first time at the age of 64. His 29-year-old bride was Elizabeth O'Rourke, whom Stamp first met in the mid-1990s at a [[pharmacy]] in [[Bondi, New South Wales|Bondi]], [[New South Wales]]. An Australian/[[Singaporean]] of [[Australia]]n and Indian-[[Singapore]]an parentage, O'Rourke was brought up in Singapore before moving to Australia in her early twenties to study [[pharmacology]]. The couple divorced on the grounds of his \"unreasonable behaviour\" in April 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7373801.stm |title=Actor Stamp and Wife Get Divorce |date=29 April 2008 |website=BBC News |accessdate=29 April 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1962\n| ''[[Billy Budd (film)|Billy Budd]]''\n| Billy Budd\n|[[Golden Globe Award for New Star of the Year - Actor]]<br />Nominated\u2014[[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]]<br />Nominated\u2014[[BAFTA Award for Best Newcomer]]\n|-\n| ''[[Term of Trial]]''\n| Mitchell\n|\n|-\n|1965\n| ''[[The Collector (1965 film)|The Collector]]''\n| Freddie Clegg\n| [[Best Actor Award (Cannes Film Festival)]]\n|-\n|1966\n| ''[[Modesty Blaise (1966 film)|Modesty Blaise]]''\n| [[Willie Garvin]]\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1967\n| ''[[Poor Cow]]''\n| Dave Fuller\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Far from the Madding Crowd (1967 film)|Far from the Madding Crowd]]''\n| Sgt. Francis 'Frank' Troy\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=3|1968\n| ''[[Blue (1968 film)|Blue]]''\n| Blue\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Spirits of the Dead]]''\n| Toby Dammit\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Teorema]]''\n| The Visitor\n|\n|-\n|1970\n| ''[[The Mind of Mr. Soames]]''\n| John Soames\n|\n|-\n|1971\n| ''[[A Season in Hell (1971 film)|A Season in Hell]]''\n| Arthur Rimbaud\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1975\n| ''[[The Divine Nymph]]''\n| Dany di Bagnasco\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Hu-man]]''\n| Terence\n|\n|-\n|1976\n| ''Striptease''\n| Alain\n|\n|-\n|1977\n| ''Black-Out''\n| Edgar Poe\n|\n|-\n|1978\n| ''[[Superman (1978 film)|Superman]]''\n| [[General Zod]]\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1979\n| ''[[Meetings with Remarkable Men (film)|Meetings with Remarkable Men]]''\n| Prince Lubovedsky\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Together?]]''\n| Henry\n|\n|-\n|1980\n| ''[[Superman II]]''\n| General Zod\n|\n|-\n|1981\n| ''[[Jules Verne's Mystery on Monster Island]]''\n| J.R. Taskinar/Skinner\n|\n|-\n|1982\n| ''[[Morte in Vaticano]]''\n| Padre Andreani, later Pope Giovanni Clemente I\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1984\n| ''[[The Hit (1984 film)|The Hit]]''\n| Willie Parker\n| Mystfest for Best Actor (Shared with [[John Hurt]] and [[Tim Roth]])\n|-\n| ''[[The Company of Wolves]]''\n| [[The Devil]]\n| Uncredited\n|-\n|rowspan=3|1986\n|''[[Legal Eagles]]''\n| Victor Taft\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Link (film)|Link]]''\n| Dr. Steven Phillip\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Hud (1986 film)|Hud]]''\n| Edward\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1987\n| ''[[The Sicilian (film)|The Sicilian]]''\n| Prince Borsa\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Wall Street (1987 film)|Wall Street]]''\n| Sir Larry Wildman\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1988\n|''[[Young Guns (film)|Young Guns]]''\n| [[John Tunstall]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Alien Nation (film)|Alien Nation]]''\n| William Harcourt\n|\n|-\n|1990\n| ''Genuine Risk''\n| Paul Hellwart\n|\n|-\n|1991\n| ''[[Prince of Shadows|Beltenebros]]''\n| Darman\n| [[Silver Bear for Best Acto