ading Role|Best Actor in a Leading Role]] \u2013 ''The Adventures of Priscilla, Queen of the Desert'' (1994)\n\n'''Independent Spirit Award'''\n*[[Independent Spirit Award for Best Male Lead|Best Male Lead]] \u2013 ''[[The Limey]]'' (1999)\n\n'''Las Vegas Film Critics Society Award'''\n*Best Actor \u2013 ''The Limey'' (1999)<ref name=\"StampAlbum\"/>\n{{col-end}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal bar|Biography}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Terence Stamp}}\n* {{IMDb name|0000654}}\n* {{Screenonline name|id=453285}}\n* {{amg name|67541}}\n* {{Tcmdb name}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box\n|title=Actors portraying [[General Zod]]\n|years=1978\u20131980<br />for ''[[Superman (1978 film)|Superman]]'' and ''[[Superman II]]''\n|before=N/A\n|after=[[Callum Blue]]<br />2003\u20132011<br />'''for ''[[Smallville]]'' '''\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Terence Stamp\n|list =\n{{Prix d'interpr\u00e9tation masculine 1960\u20131979}}\n{{Golden Globe Award for New Star of the Year Actor}}\n{{Satellite Award Best Actor Motion Picture}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stamp, Terence}}\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Webber Douglas Academy of Dramatic Art]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:Cannes Film Festival Award for Best Actor winners]]\n[[Category:Independent Spirit Award winners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Star of the Year (Actor) Golden Globe winners]]\n[[Category:People from Stepney]]\n[[Category:Silver Bear for Best Actor winners]]\n[[Category:Male actors from London]]\n[[Category:Rajneesh movement]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "ref name fixedWP:REFNAME", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Terence_Stamp"}
{"title_page": "To Live to Sing", "text_new": "{{short description|2019 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = To Live to Sing\n| image          = To Live to Sing.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Johnny Ma]]\n| producer       = Jing Wang<br>Wu Xianjian\n| writer         = Johnny Ma\n| starring       = Gan Guidan<br>Yan Xihu<br>Zhao Xiaoli\n| music          = You Jong-ho<br>Kim Ji-min<br>Reggie Ba-Pe III\n| cinematography = Matthias Delvaux\n| editing        = Ana Godoy\n| distributor    = Epicentre Films\n| released       = {{film date|2019|5|20|[[2019 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes]]|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 105 minutes\n| country        = China\n| language       = Mandarin\n}}\n\n'''''To Live to Sing''''' ({{lang-zh|c=\u6d3b\u7740\u5531\u7740|p=''Hu\u00f3zhe ch\u00e0ngzhe''|s=|t=}}) is a 2019 Chinese [[drama film]] directed by [[Johnny Ma]]. It was screened in the [[Directors' Fortnight]] section at the [[2019 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Keslassy |first1=Elsa |title=Cannes: ''Deerskin'' With Jean Dujardin to Open Directors' Fortnight |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/cannes-deerskin-with-jean-dujardin-to-open-directors-fortnight-1203180491/ |website=Variety |accessdate=19 April 2019 |language=en |date=4 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Goodfellow |first1=Melanie |title=Cannes Directors' Fortnight unveils genre-heavy 2019 selection |url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/cannes-directors-fortnight-unveils-genre-heavy-2019-selection/5138683.article |website=ScreenDaily |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref> The film won both Best Film and Best Actress at the 2019 [[Shanghai International Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shine.cn/news/metro/1906227142/ |title=Singing the feeling home |work=Shine |accessdate=7 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Zhao Xiaoli (actress)|Zhao Xiaoli]]\n* [[Gan Guidan]]\n* [[Yan Xihu]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|10225288|To Live to Sing}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:To Live To Sing}}\n[[Category:2019 films]]\n[[Category:2019 drama films]]\n[[Category:Chinese films]]\n[[Category:Chinese drama films]]\n[[Category:Chinese-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Johnny Ma]]\n{{China-film-stub}}\n{{2010s-drama-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2019 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = To Live to Sing\n| image          = To Live to Sing.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Johnny Ma]]\n| producer       = Jing Wang<br>Wu Xianjian\n| writer         = Johnny Ma\n| starring       = Gan Guidan<br>Yan Xihu<br>Zhao Xiaoli\n| music          = You Jong-ho<br>Kim Ji-min<br>Reggie Ba-Pe III\n| cinematography = Matthias Delvaux\n| editing        = Ana Godoy\n| distributor    = Epicentre Films\n| released       = {{film date|2019|5|20|[[2019 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes]]|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 105 minutes\n| country        = China\n| language       = Mandarin\n}}\n\n'''''To Live to Sing''''' ({{lang-zh|c=\u6d3b\u7740\u5531\u7740|p=''Hu\u00f3zhe ch\u00e0ngzhe''|s=|t=}}) is a 2019 Chinese [[drama film]] directed by [[Johnny Ma]]. It was screened in the [[Directors' Fortnight]] section at the [[2019 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Keslassy |first1=Elsa |title=Cannes: ''Deerskin'' With Jean Dujardin to Open Directors' Fortnight |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/cannes-deerskin-with-jean-dujardin-to-open-directors-fortnight-1203180491/ |website=Variety |accessdate=19 April 2019 |language=en |date=4 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Goodfellow |first1=Melanie |title=Cannes Directors' Fortnight unveils genre-heavy 2019 selection |url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/cannes-directors-fortnight-unveils-genre-heavy-2019-selection/5138683.article |website=ScreenDaily |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref> The film won both Best Film and Best Actress at the 2019 [[Shanghai International Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shine.cn/news/metro/1906227142/ |title=Singing the feeling home |work=Shine |accessdate=7 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Zhao Xiaoli (actress)|Zhao Xiaoli]]\n* [[Gan Guidan]]\n* [[Yan Xihu]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|10225288|To Live to Sing}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:To Live To Sing}}\n[[Category:2019 films]]\n[[Category:2019 drama films]]\n[[Category:Chinese films]]\n[[Category:Chinese drama films]]\n[[Category:Chinese-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Johnny Ma]]\n{{China-film-stub}}\n{{2010s-drama-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/To_Live_to_Sing"}
{"title_page": "Lamorna Birch", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Lamorna Birch\n| image       =\n| image_size  =\n| caption     =\n| birth_name  = Samuel John Birch\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1869|06|7|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Egremont, Merseyside|Egremont]], [[Cheshire]], [[England]]<ref name = \"wormleighton\">{{cite book| author = Austin Wormleighton|author2=Samuel John Lamorna Birch | title = A painter laureate: Lamorna Birch and his circle| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=XLdNAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA40| year = 1995| publisher = Sansom & Co.| isbn = 978-1-872971-24-7| page = 40 }}</ref>\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|1955|1|7|1869|06|7|df=yes}}\n| death_place = [[Penzance]], [[Cornwall]], [[England]]\n| death_cause =\n| residence   =\n| other_names =\n| known_for   =\n| education   =\n| employer    =\n| occupation  =\n| title       =\n| salary      =\n| networth    =\n| height      =\n| weight      =\n| term        =\n| predecessor =\n| successor   =\n| party       =\n| boards      =\n| religion    =\n| spouse      =\n| partner     =\n| children    =\n| parents     =\n| relatives   =\n| signature   =\n| website     =\n| footnotes   =\n| nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n}}\n\n'''Samuel John \"Lamorna\" Birch''', RA, RWS (7 June 1869 \u2013 7 January 1955) was an [[England|English]] artist in oils and watercolours. At the suggestion of fellow artist [[Stanhope Forbes]], Birch adopted the ''soubriquet'' \"Lamorna\" to distinguish himself from [[Lionel Birch]], an artist who was also working in the area at that time.<ref name=\u2033fr\u2033>{{cite news |last1=Ruhrmund |first1=Frank |title=This super exhibition shows why critical acclaim was correct |work=The Cornishman |date=12 July 2018 |page=15}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n[[File:Lamorna Cove - geograph.org.uk - 15105.jpg|thumb|right|[[Lamorna|Lamorna Cove]] (here in 2005) was a frequent subject for his paintings.]]\nLamorna Birch was born in [[Egremont, Merseyside|Egremont]], [[Cheshire]], [[England]].<ref name=wormleighton/> He was self-taught as an artist, except for a brief period of study at the [[Acad\u00e9mie Colarossi]] in [[Paris]] during 1895.<ref>{{cite web|title=Biography. Lamorna Birch 1869\u20131955|url=http://www.penleehouse.org.uk/artists/lamorna-birch|website=Penlee House|accessdate=12 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nBirch settled in [[Lamorna]], [[Cornwall]] in 1892, initially lodging at nearby [[Boleigh|Boleigh Farm]]. Many of his most famous pictures date from this time and the beautiful Lamorna Cove is usually their subject matter. He was attracted to Cornwall by the [[Newlyn School|Newlyn group of artists]] but he ended up starting a second group based around his adopted home of Lamorna.<ref>[https://artuk.org/discover/artworks/lamorna-cove-14258 Lamorna Cove], Lamorna Birch, BBC, accessed 12 November 2015</ref> He married Houghton (Mouse) Emily Vivian, the daughter of a mining agent from [[Camborne]] and they lived at Flagstaff Cottge, Lamorna.<ref name=\u2033fr\u2033/>\n\n==Exhibitions==\nHe exhibited at the [[Royal Academy]] from 1893, was elected as an Associate (ARA) in 1926 and made a Royal Academician (RA) in 1934, and showed more than two hundred paintings there.<ref>{{cite web|title=S.J. Lamorna Birch, R.A.|url=http://www.racollection.org.uk/ixbin/indexplus?_IXACTION_=file&_IXFILE_=templates/full/person.html&_IXTRAIL_=Academicians&person=5522|publisher=Royal Academy|accessdate=12 November 2015}}</ref> He held his first one-man exhibition at the [[Fine Art Society]] in 1906 and is said to have produced more than 20,000 pictures. Like a number of his contemporaries, he was profiled as an 'Artist of Note' in ''[[The Artist (UK magazine)|The Artist]]'' magazine, by Richard Seddon, in the June 1944 edition.\n\n* ''Shades of British Impressionism Lamorna Birch and his Circle'' was shown at [[Warrington Museum & Art Gallery]] in the Mezzanine in October 2004. This details his links with [[Henry Scott Tuke]] and [[Thomas Cooper Gotch]] and many others who settled in the [[artists' colony]] in the 1880s and 1890s. \"These painters helped to change the face of British art. Their emphasis on colour and light, truth and social realism brought about a revolution in British art.\" says the catalogue for the show.\n\n* ''Entranced By A Special Place: The Art Of S J Lamorna Birch'' \u2013 at [[Penlee House]], [[Penzance]], part of the Royal Academy's 250th anniversary celebrations.\n\n==Today==\nBirch has paintings at Penlee House and in the collection of [[Derby Museum and Art Gallery|Derby Art Gallery]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.penleehouse.org.uk/artists/samuel-birch.htm|title=Penlee House Gallery and Museum Penzance Cornwall UK|work=penleehouse.org.uk|accessdate=12 November 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010223144856/http://www.penleehouse.org.uk/artists/samuel-birch.htm|archivedate=23 February 2001|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>[https://artuk.org/search/search/search/keyword:derby-museums-and-art-gallery Winter], Lamorna Birch, accessed August 2011</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n* {{Art UK bio}}\n\n<!-- Please discuss any changes to the stubbing or categorization in the appropriate thread on the talk page before doing them. -->\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Birch, Lamorna}}\n[[Category:1869 births]]\n[[Category:1955 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century English painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century English painters]]\n[[Category:Acad\u00e9mie Colarossi alumni]]\n[[Category:Cornish painters]]\n[[Category:English male painters]]\n[[Category:Lamorna Art colony]]\n[[Category:Newlyn School of Artists]]\n[[Category:People from Wallasey]]\n[[Category:Royal Academicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Lamorna Birch\n| image       =\n| image_size  =\n| caption     =\n| birth_name  = Samuel John Birch\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1869|06|7|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Egremont, Merseyside|Egremont]], [[Cheshire]], [[England]]<ref name = \"wormleighton\">{{cite book| author = Austin Wormleighton|author2=Samuel John Lamorna Birch | title = A painter laureate: Lamorna Birch and his circle| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=XLdNAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA40| year = 1995| publisher = Sansom & Co.| isbn = 978-1-872971-24-7| page = 40 }}</ref>\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|1955|1|7|1869|06|7|df=yes}}\n| death_place = [[Penzance]], [[Cornwall]], [[England]]\n| death_cause =\n| residence   =\n| other_names =\n| known_for   =\n| education   =\n| employer    =\n| occupation  =\n| title       =\n| salary      =\n| networth    =\n| height      =\n| weight      =\n| term        =\n| predecessor =\n| successor   =\n| party       =\n| boards      =\n| religion    =\n| spouse      =\n| partner     =\n| children    =\n| parents     =\n| relatives   =\n| signature   =\n| website     =\n| footnotes   =\n| nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n}}\n\n'''Samuel John \"Lamorna\" Birch''', RA, RWS (7 June 1869 \u2013 7 January 1955) was an [[England|English]] artist in oils and watercolours. At the suggestion of fellow artist [[Stanhope Forbes]], Birch adopted the ''soubriquet'' \"Lamorna\" to distinguish himself from [[Lionel Birch]], an artist who was also working in the area at that time.<ref name=\u2033fr\u2033>{{cite news |last1=Ruhrmund |first1=Frank |title=This super exhibition shows why critical acclaim was correct |work=The Cornishman |date=12 July 2018 |page=15}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n[[File:Lamorna Cove - geograph.org.uk - 15105.jpg|thumb|right|[[Lamorna|Lamorna Cove]] (here in 2005) was a frequent subject for his paintings.]]\nLamorna Birch was born in [[Egremont, Merseyside|Egremont]], [[Cheshire]], [[England]].<ref name=wormleighton/> He was self-taught as an artist, except for a brief period of study at the [[Acad\u00e9mie Colarossi]] in [[Paris]] during 1895.<ref>{{cite web|title=Biography. Lamorna Birch 1869\u20131955|url=http://www.penleehouse.org.uk/artists/lamorna-birch|website=Penlee House|accessdate=12 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nBirch settled in [[Lamorna]], [[Cornwall]] in 1892, initially lodging at nearby [[Boleigh|Boleigh Farm]]. Many of his most famous pictures date from this time and the beautiful Lamorna Cove is usually their subject matter. He was attracted to Cornwall by the [[Newlyn School|Newlyn group of artists]] but he ended up starting a second group based around his adopted home of Lamorna.<ref>[https://artuk.org/discover/artworks/lamorna-cove-14258 Lamorna Cove], Lamorna Birch, BBC, accessed 12 November 2015</ref> He married Houghton (Mouse) Emily Vivian, the daughter of a mining agent from [[Camborne]] and they lived at Flagstaff Cottge, Lamorna.<ref name=\u2033fr\u2033/>\n\n==Exhibitions==\nHe exhibited at the [[Royal Academy]] from 1893, was elected as an Associate (ARA) in 1926 and made a Royal Academician (RA) in 1934, and showed more than two hundred paintings there.<ref>{{cite web|title=S.J. Lamorna Birch, R.A.|url=http://www.racollection.org.uk/ixbin/indexplus?_IXACTION_=file&_IXFILE_=templates/full/person.html&_IXTRAIL_=Academicians&person=5522|publisher=Royal Academy|accessdate=12 November 2015}}</ref> He held his first one-man exhibition at the [[Fine Art Society]] in 1906 and is said to have produced more than 20,000 pictures. Like a number of his contemporaries, he was profiled as an 'Artist of Note' in ''[[The Artist (UK magazine)|The Artist]]'' magazine, by Richard Seddon, in the June 1944 edition.\n\n* ''Shades of British Impressionism Lamorna Birch and his Circle'' was shown at [[Warrington Museum & Art Gallery]] in the Mezzanine in October 2004. This details his links with [[Henry Scott Tuke]] and [[Thomas Cooper Gotch]] and many others who settled in the [[artists' colony]] in the 1880s and 1890s. \"These painters helped to change the face of British art. Their emphasis on colour and light, truth and social realism brought about a revolution in British art.\" says the catalogue for the show.\n\n* ''Entranced By A Special Place: The Art Of S J Lamorna Birch'' \u2013 at [[Penlee House]], [[Penzance]], part of the Royal Academy's 250th anniversary celebrations.\n\n==Today==\nBirch has paintings at Penlee House and in the collection of [[Derby Museum and Art Gallery|Derby Art Gallery]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.penleehouse.org.uk/artists/samuel-birch.htm|title=Penlee House Gallery and Museum Penzance Cornwall UK|work=penleehouse.org.uk|accessdate=12 November 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010223144856/http://www.penleehouse.org.uk/artists/samuel-birch.htm|archivedate=23 February 2001|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>[https://artuk.org/search/search/search/keyword:derby-museums-and-art-gallery Winter], Lamorna Birch, accessed August 2011</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Art UK bio}}\n\n<!-- Please discuss any changes to the stubbing or categorization in the appropriate thread on the talk page before doing them. -->\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Birch, Lamorna}}\n[[Category:1869 births]]\n[[Category:1955 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century English painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century English painters]]\n[[Category:Acad\u00e9mie Colarossi alumni]]\n[[Category:Cornish painters]]\n[[Category:English male painters]]\n[[Category:Lamorna Art colony]]\n[[Category:Newlyn School of Artists]]\n[[Category:People from Wallasey]]\n[[Category:Royal Academicians]]\n", "name_user": "Gazamp", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:AddedPortal:Cornwall", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lamorna_Birch"}
{"title_page": "Thorne, Cornwall", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n[[File:Thorne Farm - geograph.org.uk - 929453.jpg|thumb|Thorne Farm, Whitstone]]\n'''Thorne''' is the name of two hamlets in north [[Cornwall]], England, United Kingdom. One is on the A3073 road near [[Bude]] and the other near [[Whitstone]]. Thorne, Whitstone, was a manor in medieval times and had in 1086 land for one plough and 20 acres of pasture.<ref>Thorn, Caroline, et al. (eds.) (1979) ''Cornwall'' (Domesday Book; 10.) Chichester: Phillimore; entry 5,5,8</ref><ref>Ordnance Survey (1946) ''One-inch Map of England and Wales; Bude, sheet 174''</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|Cornwall}}\n\n[[Category:Hamlets in Cornwall]]\n[[Category:Manors in Cornwall]]\n\n\n{{Cornwall-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n[[File:Thorne Farm - geograph.org.uk - 929453.jpg|thumb|Thorne Farm, Whitstone]]\n'''Thorne''' is the name of two hamlets in north [[Cornwall]], England, United Kingdom. One is on the A3073 road near [[Bude]] and the other near [[Whitstone]]. Thorne, Whitstone, was a manor in medieval times and had in 1086 land for one plough and 20 acres of pasture.<ref>Thorn, Caroline, et al. (eds.) (1979) ''Cornwall'' (Domesday Book; 10.) Chichester: Phillimore; entry 5,5,8</ref><ref>Ordnance Survey (1946) ''One-inch Map of England and Wales; Bude, sheet 174''</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|Cornwall}}\n\n[[Category:Hamlets in Cornwall]]\n[[Category:Manors in Cornwall]]\n\n\n{{Cornwall-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Gazamp", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:AddedPortal:Cornwall", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thorne,_Cornwall"}
{"title_page": "Tramontane (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2016 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Tramontane\n| image          = Tramontane 2016.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Vatche Boulghourjian]]\n| producer       = Georges Schoucair<br>Caroline Oliveira<br>Gabrielle Dumon\n| writer         = Vatche Boulghourjian\n| starring       = Barakat Jabbour\n| music          = Cynthia Zaven\n| cinematography = James Lee Phelan\n| editing        = [[Nadia Ben Rachid]]\n| distributor    = Ad Vitam {{small|(France)}}\n| released       = {{Film date|2016|5|17|[[2016 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes]]|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 105 minutes\n| country        = Lebanon<br>France<br>Qatar<br>United Arab Emirates\n| language       = Arabic\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''Tramontane''''' ({{lang-ar|'''Rabi'h'''}}) is a 2016 Lebanese [[drama film]] directed by [[Vatche Boulghourjian]]. It premiered in the [[International Critics' Week]] section of the [[2016 Cannes Film Festival]] where it was awarded the Grand Rail d'Or Audience Award.<ref name=\"Semaine\">{{cite web |url=http://www.semainedelacritique.com/selection.php |title=Selection of the 55th International Critics' Week |accessdate=18 April 2016 |work=Semaine de la Critique}}</ref><ref name=\"deadline-semaine\">{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2016/04/critics-week-2016-lineup-full-list-cannes-film-festival-1201739395/ |title=Cannes: Critics\u2019 Week 2016 Lineup \u2013 Full List |accessdate=18 April 2016 |date=18 April 2016 |author=Nancy Tartaglione |work=Deadline Hollywood}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* Barakat Jabbour as Rabih\n* Julia Kassar as Samar\n* Toufic Barakat as Hisham\n* Michel Adabachi as Wissam\n* Abido Bacha as Mounir\n* Odette Makhlouf as Hana\n* Georges Diab as Nabil\n\n==Reception==\nOn [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 86% based on 7 reviews, and an [[average rating]] of 5.6/10.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/tramontane |title=Tramontane (2016) |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]] |accessdate=8 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|5590712|Tramontane}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tramontane}}\n[[Category:2016 films]]\n[[Category:2016 drama films]]\n[[Category:Lebanese films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:Qatari films]]\n[[Category:Emirati films]]\n[[Category:Arabic-language films]]\n[[Category:2016 directorial debut films]]\n[[Category:Films about blind people]]\n[[Category:Lebanese drama films]]\n{{Lebanon-film-stub}}\n{{2010s-drama-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2016 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Tramontane\n| image          = Tramontane 2016.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Vatche Boulghourjian]]\n| producer       = Georges Schoucair<br>Caroline Oliveira<br>Gabrielle Dumon\n| writer         = Vatche Boulghourjian\n| starring       = Barakat Jabbour\n| music          = Cynthia Zaven\n| cinematography = James Lee Phelan\n| editing        = [[Nadia Ben Rachid]]\n| distributor    = Ad Vitam {{small|(France)}}\n| released       = {{Film date|2016|5|17|[[2016 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes]]|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 105 minutes\n| country        = Lebanon<br>France<br>Qatar<br>United Arab Emirates\n| language       = Arabic\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''Tramontane''''' ({{lang-ar|'''Rabi'h'''}}) is a 2016 Lebanese [[drama film]] directed by [[Vatche Boulghourjian]]. It premiered in the [[International Critics' Week]] section of the [[2016 Cannes Film Festival]] where it was awarded the Grand Rail d'Or Audience Award.<ref name=\"Semaine\">{{cite web |url=http://www.semainedelacritique.com/selection.php |title=Selection of the 55th International Critics' Week |accessdate=18 April 2016 |work=Semaine de la Critique}}</ref><ref name=\"deadline-semaine\">{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2016/04/critics-week-2016-lineup-full-list-cannes-film-festival-1201739395/ |title=Cannes: Critics\u2019 Week 2016 Lineup \u2013 Full List |accessdate=18 April 2016 |date=18 April 2016 |author=Nancy Tartaglione |work=Deadline Hollywood}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* Barakat Jabbour as Rabih\n* Julia Kassar as Samar\n* Toufic Barakat as Hisham\n* Michel Adabachi as Wissam\n* Abido Bacha as Mounir\n* Odette Makhlouf as Hana\n* Georges Diab as Nabil\n\n==Reception==\nOn [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 86% based on 7 reviews, and an [[average rating]] of 5.6/10.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/tramontane |title=Tramontane (2016) |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]] |accessdate=8 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|5590712|Tramontane}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tramontane}}\n[[Category:2016 films]]\n[[Category:2016 drama films]]\n[[Category:Lebanese films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:Qatari films]]\n[[Category:Emirati films]]\n[[Category:Arabic-language films]]\n[[Category:2016 directorial debut films]]\n[[Category:Films about blind people]]\n[[Category:Lebanese drama films]]\n{{Lebanon-film-stub}}\n{{2010s-drama-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tramontane_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Medical Licentiate Society of Hong Kong", "text_new": "{{Infobox organization\n| alt = Asclepius serpent-entwined Bauhinia anchor surrounded by earthly blue circle\n| logo = File:The Medical Licentiate Society of Hong Kong.jpg\n| logo_size = 250x250px\n| logo_caption = Licentiate Society logo\n| abbreviation = Licentiate Society<br>LMCHK Soc\n| formation = {{Start date and age|2017|6|15}}\n| type = [[Nonprofit organization]]\n| status = Company limited by guarantee\n| headquarters = [[Hong Kong]]\n| region = Worldwide\n| website = https://lmchk.org\n}}{{Infobox Chinese\n| c = \n| t = \u9999\u6e2f\u57f7\u7167\u91ab\u751f\u91ab\u5b78\u6703\n| s = \n| p = \n| j = \n| mi = \n| ci = \n| altname = \n}}\nThe '''Medical Licentiate Society of Hong Kong''' ('''Licentiate Society''', Chinese: \u9999\u6e2f\u57f7\u7167\u91ab\u751f\u91ab\u5b78\u6703, and branded also as '''LMCHK SOC''') is an independent, non-profit, recognized professional body representing doctors that have graduated from medical schools outside of [[Hong Kong]] and that have attained (or are in the process of attaining) medical licensure in Hong Kong.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ha.org.hk/visitor/ha_visitor_index.asp?Content_ID=635&Lang=ENG&Dimension=100&Parent_ID=10129|title=Local Professional Bodies|last=|first=|date=|website=Hospital Authority of Hong Kong|series=Healthcare Professionals|location=Hong Kong|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The group was founded in 2017 and incorporated in 2019. It has offices in Central, Hong Kong. It is the only incorporated organization dedicated to such doctors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.icris.cr.gov.hk/csci/login_i.do?loginType=iguest&OPT_01=1&OPT_02=1&OPT_03=1&OPT_04=1&OPT_05=1&OPT_06=1&OPT_07=1&OPT_08=1&OPT_09=1|title=Cyber Search Centre of the Companies Registry|last=|first=|date=|website=Hong Kong Companies Registry|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nThe member doctors graduated from [[medical school]]s outside of Hong Kong, attained [[Medical license|medical licensure]] in their original jurisdiction, and then successfully cleared the qualification requirements for registering as a medical practitioner in Hong Kong. \n\nBefore non-local medical graduates can become registered medical practitioners in Hong Kong, they are required to attain a license from the Medical Council of Hong Kong (i.e., the [[Licentiate of the Medical Council of Hong Kong]] or LMCHK qualification).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mchk.org.hk/english/registration/full_registration.html|title=Registration of Medical Practitioners|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 December 2019}}</ref> The pathway to earn the qualification requires passing a rigorous [[Hong Kong Medical Licensing Examination|Hong Kong Medical Licensing Examination (HKMLE)]] and undergoing a period of training or local work experience.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elegislation.gov.hk/hk/cap161?xpid=ID_1438402758513_002|title=Licensing Examination|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://leip.mchk.org.hk/EN/aexam_III.html|title=Period of Assessment|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 December 2019}}</ref> LMCHK doctors are thus both licensed and registered in Hong Kong.\n\nPrior to 1997, the LMCHK doctors consisted overwhelmingly of graduates from Mainland China. The pre-1997 [[British Hong Kong|colonial government]] exempted graduates of commonwealth countries from having to sit for a licensing exam or having to serve additional training. After 1997, all non-local graduates were required to earn the LMCHK licensure in order to register to practice in Hong Kong.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://leip.mchk.org.hk/EN/g_info.html|title=General information about becoming a registered medical practitioner|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 December 2019}}</ref> Consequently, the geographic and ethnic diversity of LMCHK doctors has increased particularly in the last several years.\n\n== History ==\nThe rigorous requirements to become an LMCHK doctor has given the group a common bond.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/article/975687/foreign-doctors-test-too-tough|title=Foreign doctors' test 'too tough'|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 December 2019}}</ref> With the growing size and diversity of LMCHK doctors post-1997, interest grew within the LMCHK community to meet up. To this end, there were periodic social events throughout the years from 1997 to 2016. The Licentiate Society traces its formation to 15 June 2017, when the doctors started a popular WhatsApp group and began meeting regularly.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lmchk.org/about-us|title=Origins of the Licentiate Society|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn this same day, 11 members of the LMCHK community held a happy hour social. The group continued to grow and hold regular meet-ups, dinners, and other events. In August 2019, the members outnumbered the WhatsApp limit of 256 people. To address the overflow, they formed additional groups.\n\nThe quarterly events (and more) have been held continuously since June 2017. On 26 November 2019, the group incorporated as a [[Nonprofit organization|nonprofit]] company [[Private company limited by guarantee|limited by guarantee]] with the name The Medical Licentiate Society of Hong Kong.\n\nThe Licentiate Society has LMCHK doctors from over 20 different licensing jurisdictions including (in order by relative numbers of doctors): UK, Mainland China, Australia, Ireland, USA, Canada, South Africa, Chinese Taipei, Singapore, Belgium, India, Korea, Nepal, Netherland-Antilles, New Zealand, Poland, Portugal, Russia, United Arab Emirates, and Venezuela.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lmchk.org/about-us|title=Diversity among the LMCHK|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Purpose ==\nThe Licentiate Society's aims include:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lmchk.org/about-us|title=Purpose of the Licentiate Society|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hk01.com/\u793e\u6703\u65b0\u805e/431757/\u6b66\u6f22\u80ba\u708e-\u75ab\u60c5\u8086\u8650\u7919\u4f86\u6e2f\u4fe1\u5fc3-\u903e8\u6210\u6d77\u5916\u91ab\u751f\u5b58\u8ca0\u9762\u89c0\u611f|title=\u3010\u6b66\u6f22\u80ba\u708e\u3011\u75ab\u60c5\u8086\u8650\u7919\u4f86\u6e2f\u4fe1\u5fc3 \u903e8\u6210\u6d77\u5916\u91ab\u751f\u5b58\u8ca0\u9762\u89c0\u611f|last=\u9673\u6dd1\u971e|first=|date=2020-02-07|website=\u9999\u6e2f01|language=zh-HK|type=Licentiate Society published survey results of Hong Kong\u2019s non-locally trained (LMCHK) doctors on the impact of the coronavirus outbreak|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.mingpao.com/ins/%e6%96%87%e6%91%98/article/20200224/s00022/1582451389324/%e9%86%ab%e7%95%8c%e4%ba%ba%e6%89%8b%e8%88%87%e8%b3%87%e6%ad%b7%e4%b8%8d%e8%b6%b3%e5%b0%87%e5%8a%a0%e5%8a%87-%e7%96%ab%e6%83%85%e5%b0%8d%e6%8b%9b%e6%94%ac%e6%b5%b7%e5%a4%96%e9%86%ab%e7%94%9f%e7%9a%84%e5%bd%b1%e9%9f%bf%ef%bc%88%e6%96%87-%e6%b1%9f%e5%ae%b6%e9%8a%98%ef%bc%89|title=\u91ab\u754c\u4eba\u624b\u8207\u8cc7\u6b77\u4e0d\u8db3\u5c07\u52a0\u5287\u2014\u2014\u75ab\u60c5\u5c0d\u62db\u652c\u6d77\u5916\u91ab\u751f\u7684\u5f71\u97ff\uff08\u6587\uff1a\u6c5f\u5bb6\u9298\uff09 (09:00) - 20200224 - \u6587\u6458|website=\u660e\u5831\u65b0\u805e\u7db2 - \u5373\u6642\u65b0\u805e instant news|language=zh-hant|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref>\n\n* Nurtures the needs of the LMCHK community through social events and medical education.\n* Represents LMCHK community's interests in and outside of Hong Kong\n* Supports the efforts of candidates sitting for the HKMLE, including holding exam review sessions\n* Endorses public education and engagement<ref>{{Citation|last=|first=|title=Webinar - Pandemic Strategy: Staying Healthy during Covid-19|date=2020-03-25|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8rzrIFZ_QUo|volume=|pages=|publisher=Spanish Chamber of Commerce in Hong Kong|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n* Promotes the highest standards of healthcare, professionalism, safety, and education\n* Encourages working with other medical practitioners and doctors and community organizations in realizing it objectives\n\n== Governance ==\nThe Licentiate Society's governing body is the [[Council]] and consists of 9 Council Members, who serve as its [[board of directors]]. Three Council Members hold officer positions as follows: President, Honorary Secretary, and Honorary Treasurer.\n\n== Membership ==\nThere are 4 classes of members: Full, Associate, Honorary, and Corporate. Only Full Members may vote and hold office.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lmchk.org/membership#b71cc57a-46af-4cb1-a3a8-954f32fb5bf7|title=Membership|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Committees ==\nThe Licentiate Society has 3 approved [[Committee|committees]], which consist of the following: Member Services, [[Medical education|Medical Education]], and Industry Relations.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://lmchk.org Official website]\n\n[[Category:Medical associations in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Professional associations based in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Medical and health organisations based in Hong Kong]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox organization\n| alt = Asclepius serpent-entwined Bauhinia anchor surrounded by earthly blue circle\n| logo = File:The Medical Licentiate Society of Hong Kong.jpg\n| logo_size = 250x250px\n| logo_caption = Licentiate Society logo\n| abbreviation = Licentiate Society<br>LMCHK Soc\n| formation = {{Start date and age|2017|6|15}}\n| type = [[Nonprofit organization]]\n| status = Company limited by guarantee\n| headquarters = [[Hong Kong]]\n| region = Worldwide\n| website = https://lmchk.org\n}}{{Infobox Chinese\n| c = \n| t = \u9999\u6e2f\u57f7\u7167\u91ab\u751f\u91ab\u5b78\u6703\n| s = \n| p = \n| j = \n| mi = \n| ci = \n| altname = \n}}\nThe '''Medical Licentiate Society of Hong Kong''' ('''Licentiate Society''', Chinese: \u9999\u6e2f\u57f7\u7167\u91ab\u751f\u91ab\u5b78\u6703, and branded also as '''LMCHK SOC''') is an independent, non-profit, recognized professional body representing doctors that have graduated from medical schools outside of [[Hong Kong]] and that have attained (or are in the process of attaining) medical licensure in Hong Kong.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ha.org.hk/visitor/ha_visitor_index.asp?Content_ID=635&Lang=ENG&Dimension=100&Parent_ID=10129|title=Local Professional Bodies|last=|first=|date=|website=Hospital Authority of Hong Kong|series=Healthcare Professionals|location=Hong Kong|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The group was founded in 2017 and incorporated in 2019. It has offices in Central, Hong Kong. It is the only incorporated organization dedicated to such doctors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.icris.cr.gov.hk/csci/login_i.do?loginType=iguest&OPT_01=1&OPT_02=1&OPT_03=1&OPT_04=1&OPT_05=1&OPT_06=1&OPT_07=1&OPT_08=1&OPT_09=1|title=Cyber Search Centre of the Companies Registry|last=|first=|date=|website=Hong Kong Companies Registry|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nThe member doctors graduated from [[medical school]]s outside of Hong Kong, attained [[Medical license|medical licensure]] in their original jurisdiction, and then successfully cleared the qualification requirements for registering as a medical practitioner in Hong Kong. \n\nBefore non-local medical graduates can become registered medical practitioners in Hong Kong, they are required to attain a license from the Medical Council of Hong Kong (i.e., the [[Licentiate of the Medical Council of Hong Kong]] or LMCHK qualification).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mchk.org.hk/english/registration/full_registration.html|title=Registration of Medical Practitioners|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 December 2019}}</ref> The pathway to earn the qualification requires passing a rigorous [[Hong Kong Medical Licensing Examination|Hong Kong Medical Licensing Examination (HKMLE)]] and undergoing a period of training or local work experience.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elegislation.gov.hk/hk/cap161?xpid=ID_1438402758513_002|title=Licensing Examination|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://leip.mchk.org.hk/EN/aexam_III.html|title=Period of Assessment|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 December 2019}}</ref> LMCHK doctors are thus both licensed and registered in Hong Kong.\n\nPrior to 1997, the LMCHK doctors consisted overwhelmingly of graduates from Mainland China. The pre-1997 [[British Hong Kong|colonial government]] exempted graduates of commonwealth countries from having to sit for a licensing exam or having to serve additional training. After 1997, all non-local graduates were required to earn the LMCHK licensure in order to register to practice in Hong Kong.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://leip.mchk.org.hk/EN/g_info.html|title=General information about becoming a registered medical practitioner|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 December 2019}}</ref> Consequently, the geographic and ethnic diversity of LMCHK doctors has increased particularly in the last several years.\n\n== History ==\nThe rigorous requirements to become an LMCHK doctor has given the group a common bond.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/article/975687/foreign-doctors-test-too-tough|title=Foreign doctors' test 'too tough'|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 December 2019}}</ref> With the growing size and diversity of LMCHK doctors post-1997, interest grew within the LMCHK community to meet up. To this end, there were periodic social events throughout the years from 1997 to 2016. The Licentiate Society traces its formation to 15 June 2017, when the doctors started a popular WhatsApp group and began meeting regularly.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lmchk.org/about-us|title=Origins of the Licentiate Society|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn this same day, 11 members of the LMCHK community held a happy hour social. The group continued to grow and hold regular meet-ups, dinners, and other events. In August 2019, the members outnumbered the WhatsApp limit of 256 people. To address the overflow, they formed additional groups.\n\nThe quarterly events (and more) have been held continuously since June 2017. On 26 November 2019, the group incorporated as a [[Nonprofit organization|nonprofit]] company [[Private company limited by guarantee|limited by guarantee]] with the name The Medical Licentiate Society of Hong Kong.\n\nThe Licentiate Society has LMCHK doctors from over 20 different licensing jurisdictions including (in order by relative numbers of doctors): UK, Mainland China, Australia, Ireland, USA, Canada, South Africa, Chinese Taipei, Singapore, Belgium, India, Korea, Nepal, Netherland-Antilles, New Zealand, Poland, Portugal, Russia, United Arab Emirates, and Venezuela.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lmchk.org/about-us|title=Diversity among the LMCHK|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Purpose ==\nThe Licentiate Society's aims include:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lmchk.org/about-us|title=Purpose of the Licentiate Society|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hk01.com/\u793e\u6703\u65b0\u805e/431757/\u6b66\u6f22\u80ba\u708e-\u75ab\u60c5\u8086\u8650\u7919\u4f86\u6e2f\u4fe1\u5fc3-\u903e8\u6210\u6d77\u5916\u91ab\u751f\u5b58\u8ca0\u9762\u89c0\u611f|title=\u3010\u6b66\u6f22\u80ba\u708e\u3011\u75ab\u60c5\u8086\u8650\u7919\u4f86\u6e2f\u4fe1\u5fc3 \u903e8\u6210\u6d77\u5916\u91ab\u751f\u5b58\u8ca0\u9762\u89c0\u611f|last=\u9673\u6dd1\u971e|first=|date=2020-02-07|website=\u9999\u6e2f01|language=zh-HK|type=Licentiate Society published survey results of Hong Kong\u2019s non-locally trained (LMCHK) doctors on the impact of the coronavirus outbreak|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.mingpao.com/ins/%e6%96%87%e6%91%98/article/20200224/s00022/1582451389324/%e9%86%ab%e7%95%8c%e4%ba%ba%e6%89%8b%e8%88%87%e8%b3%87%e6%ad%b7%e4%b8%8d%e8%b6%b3%e5%b0%87%e5%8a%a0%e5%8a%87-%e7%96%ab%e6%83%85%e5%b0%8d%e6%8b%9b%e6%94%ac%e6%b5%b7%e5%a4%96%e9%86%ab%e7%94%9f%e7%9a%84%e5%bd%b1%e9%9f%bf%ef%bc%88%e6%96%87-%e6%b1%9f%e5%ae%b6%e9%8a%98%ef%bc%89|title=\u91ab\u754c\u4eba\u624b\u8207\u8cc7\u6b77\u4e0d\u8db3\u5c07\u52a0\u5287\u2014\u2014\u75ab\u60c5\u5c0d\u62db\u652c\u6d77\u5916\u91ab\u751f\u7684\u5f71\u97ff\uff08\u6587\uff1a\u6c5f\u5bb6\u9298\uff09 (09:00) - 20200224 - \u6587\u6458|website=\u660e\u5831\u65b0\u805e\u7db2 - \u5373\u6642\u65b0\u805e instant news|language=zh-hant|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref>\n\n* Nurtures the needs of the LMCHK community through social events and medical education.\n* Represents LMCHK community's interests in and outside of Hong Kong\n* Supports the efforts of candidates sitting for the HKMLE, including holding exam review sessions\n* Endorses public education and engagement<ref>{{Citation|title=Webinar - Pandemic Strategy: Staying Healthy during Covid-19|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8rzrIFZ_QUo|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n* Promotes the highest standards of healthcare, professionalism, safety, and education\n* Encourages working with other medical practitioners and doctors and community organizations in realizing it objectives\n\n== Governance ==\nThe Licentiate Society's governing body is the [[Council]] and consists of 9 Council Members, who serve as its [[board of directors]]. Three Council Members hold officer positions as follows: President, Honorary Secretary, and Honorary Treasurer.\n\n== Membership ==\nThere are 4 classes of members: Full, Associate, Honorary, and Corporate. Only Full Members may vote and hold office.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lmchk.org/membership#b71cc57a-46af-4cb1-a3a8-954f32fb5bf7|title=Membership|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Committees ==\nThe Licentiate Society has 3 approved [[Committee|committees]], which consist of the following: Member Services, [[Medical education|Medical Education]], and Industry Relations.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://lmchk.org Official website]\n\n[[Category:Medical associations in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Professional associations based in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Medical and health organisations based in Hong Kong]]\n", "name_user": "Fluidix", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePurpose", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Medical_Licentiate_Society_of_Hong_Kong"}
